n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 227765\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nFoster and his wife, Aesook Byon, live in [[Naperville, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/sleuth/2009/01/three_house_members_wearing_ne.html |work=The Washington Post |title=Three House Members Wearing New Rings in the 111th}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://query.nictusa.com/cgi-bin/dcdev/forms/C00435099/746348/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120717042556/http://query.nictusa.com/cgi-bin/dcdev/forms/C00435099/746348/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-17 |title=Foster, Bill \u2013 Statement of Candidacy |publisher=Federal Elections Commission |date=2011-09-29 |accessdate=2011-10-04 }}</ref> He has two adult children from his first marriage.<ref name=\"chitribmay\" /> Foster has lived and worked in northern Illinois ([[Naperville, Illinois|Naperville]], [[Geneva, Illinois|Geneva]], [[Batavia, Illinois|Batavia]], and [[St. Charles, Illinois|St. Charles]]) since 1984.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130130221927/http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news%2Fpolitics&id=8846465 Biggert, Foster square off in 11th Dist. debate], [[ABC 7 Chicago]], October 13, 2012, complete video\n*[http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20120918/submitted/309189867/ 2012 candidate questionnaire] at the ''Daily Herald''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141020185327/http://elections.nwherald.com/candidate/63/ 2012 candidate questionnaire] at the ''Northwest Herald''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140202172054/http://www.suntimes.com/news/elections/questionnaires/2749584,14CDFoster.article 2012 candidate questionnaire] at the ''Chicago Sun-Times''\n*[http://chicagotonight.wttw.com/2012/02/23/bill-foster-q 2012 candidate questionnaire] at WTTW ''Chicago Tonight''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121123061249/http://abclocal.go.com/wls/feature?section=news%2Fpolitics%2Flocal_elections&id=8538936 2012 candidate questionnaire and video] at ABC 7 Chicago\n\n==External links==\n* [http://foster.house.gov/ Congressman Bill Foster] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.billfoster.com/ Bill Foster for Congress]\n*{{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Illinois/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Bill_Foster_%5BD-11%5D|Bill Foster}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=F000454 | votesmart=101632 | fec=H8IL14067 | congress=bill-foster/F000454 }}\n; Scientific\n* {{Worldcat id|np-foster,%20g%20william|G. William Foster}} academic papers\n* [http://research.ieeexplore.ieee.org/AuthorNetwork/AuthorSearchResult.jsp?authorid=43604771 IEEE \u2013 G. William Foster]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} academic journal papers\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state    = Illinois\n|district = 14\n|before   = [[Dennis Hastert]]\n|after    = [[Randy Hultgren]]\n|years    = 2008\u20132011}}\n|-\n{{US House succession box\n|state    = Illinois\n|district = 11\n|before   = [[Adam Kinzinger]]\n|years    = 2013\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Walberg]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=148th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Justin Amash]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{IL-FedRep}}\n{{Current members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foster, Bill}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Madison, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Madison, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Naperville, Illinois]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Bill Foster\n|image        = Bill Foster, Official Portrait, 113th Congress.jpg\n|office       = Member of the<br>[[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Illinois]]\n| term_start1 = January 3, 2013\n| term_end1 =\n| predecessor1 = [[Judy Biggert]] (Redistricting)\n| successor1 =\n|constituency1 = [[Illinois's 11th congressional district|11th district]]\n| term_start2 = March 8, 2008\n| term_end2 = January 3, 2011\n| predecessor2 = [[Dennis Hastert]]\n| successor2 = [[Randy Hultgren]]\n|constituency2 = [[Illinois's 14th congressional district|14th district]]\n|birth_name   = George William Foster\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|10|7}}\n|birth_place  = [[Madison, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|spouse       = Ann (Divorced 1996)<br>{{marriage|Aesook Byon|2008}}\n|children     = 2\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education    = [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Harvard University]] ([[Master of Science|MS]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n|website      = {{url|foster.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''George William Foster''' (born October 7, 1955) is an American businessman, physicist, and [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|Illinois|11}}, winning the seat in 2012.<ref name=cbs-6-11-2012>{{cite web|title=Judy Biggert Concedes Race To Bill Foster|work=CBS Chicago|date=Nov 6, 2012|url=http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2012/11/06/biggert-concedes-race-to-foster/}}</ref> He was previously the U.S. Representative for {{ushr|Illinois|14}} from 2008 to 2011. He is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nFoster was born in 1955 in [[Madison, Wisconsin]]. As a teenager, he attended [[James Madison Memorial High School]] He received his [[bachelor's degree]] in [[physics]] from the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]] in 1976 and his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in physics from [[Harvard University]] in 1983.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/bill-foster/gIQAnjxyDP_print.html?noredirect=on|title=Bill Foster - Who Runs Government|work=The Washington Post|access-date=August 10, 2018}}</ref> The title of his doctoral dissertation is \"An experimental limit on proton decay: <math>p \\rightarrow \\mathrm{positron} + \\pi^0</math>.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Foster |first1=George William |title=A Experimental Limit on Proton Decay: Proton ---&gt; Positron + Neutral Pion |date=1983 |publisher=Harvard University |url=https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1983PhDT........48F/abstract |accessdate=20 November 2019 |language=en |format=Dissertation}}</ref>\n\nAt age 19, Foster and his younger brother Fred started a business in their basement with $500 from their parents. The company, Electronic Theatre Controls (ETC), now has over 650 employees worldwide and manufactures over half of the theater lighting equipment in the United States. Installations include [[Broadway theatre|Broadway shows]], [[Rolling Stones]] tours, [[opera house]]s, [[Super Bowl halftime shows]], and at schools, churches, and community centers around the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.etcconnect.com/installations.aspx |title=Lighting Solutions from ETC |accessdate=2008-03-11 |author=Electronic Theatre Controls |year=2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225105141/http://www.etcconnect.com/installations.aspx |archivedate=25 February 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Physics career==\nAfter completing his Ph.D., Foster moved to the [[Fox Valley (Illinois)|Fox Valley]] with his family to pursue a career in [[Particle physics|high-energy (particle) physics]] at [[Fermilab]], a [[United States Department of Energy National Laboratories|Department of Energy National Laboratory]]. During Foster's 22 years at Fermilab he participated in several projects, including the design of equipment and data analysis software for the [[Collider Detector at Fermilab|CDF Detector]], which were used in the discovery of the [[top quark]], and the management of the design and construction of a 3&nbsp;km Anti-Proton Recycler Ring for the Main Injector.<ref>{{cite web|last=Foster|first=G. William|title=[4C.01] The Fermilab Permanent Magnet Antiproton Recycler Ring|work=The 1997 Particle Accelerator Conference Meeting Program Vancouver BC, Canada|publisher=Fermilab|date=May 12\u201316, 1997|url=http://flux.aps.org/meetings/YR97/BAPSPAC97/abs/S240001.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030718115424/http://flux.aps.org/meetings/YR97/BAPSPAC97/abs/S240001.html|archive-date=July 18, 2003|url-status=live|access-date=February 24, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2006/0501/p02s01-stss.html |title=Physicists hope to win support for new subatomic smasher |author=Spotts, Peter N. |newspaper=Christian Science Monitor |date=2004-05-01 |accessdate=2008-03-11}}</ref>\n\nHe has been elected a fellow of the [[American Physical Society]], was on the team receiving the 1989 [[Bruno Rossi Prize]] for [[cosmic ray]] physics for the discovery of the [[neutrino]] burst from the [[supernova]] [[SN 1987A]], received the Particle Accelerator Technology Prize from the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]], and was awarded an Energy Conservation award from the [[United States Department of Energy]] for his application of permanent [[magnet]]s for [[Fermilab]]'s [[Particle accelerator|accelerators]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aas.org/head/rossi/rossi.recip.html#E |title=HEAD AAS Rossi Prize Winners |author=American Astronomical Society \u2013 High Energy Astrophysics Division |year=1989 |accessdate=2008-03-11 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080406082614/http://www.aas.org/head/rossi/rossi.recip.html |archivedate=6 April 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2008 special\n{{Main|2008 Illinois's 14th congressional district special election}}\nOn November 26, 2007, former House Republican Speaker [[Dennis Hastert|J. Dennis Hastert]] resigned as the Representative from Illinois' 14th congressional district. Foster announced his candidacy to fill the vacancy on May 30, 2007.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:NewsBank:ECNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=119D38CBB4CC8A60&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=AA98CDC331574F0ABEAFF732B33DC0B2 |title=Geneva man seeks position in Congress |publisher=Courier News (Elgin, IL) |date=2007-05-31 |accessdate=2008-03-11}}</ref>\nIn the March special election, Foster defeated Republican nominee and Hastert-endorsed candidate [[Jim Oberweis]] 53%\u201347%.<ref name=\"General Election\">{{cite news |url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/files/elections/2008/by_county/IL_Page_0308.html?SITE=ILCHTELN&SECTION=POLITICS |title=General election results |date=2008-03-08 |newspaper=Chicago Tribune}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=IL \u2013 District 14 \u2013 Special Election|work=Our Campaigns|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=403895}}</ref>\n\n;2008 general\n{{Main|2008 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois#District 14}}\nIn November, Oberweis ran against Foster again in a rematch. Foster won re-election to a full term 58%\u201342%.<ref>{{cite web|title=IL \u2013 District 14|work=Our Campaigns\n|url =http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=343142}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{Main|2010 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois#District 14}}\nFoster was challenged by Republican nominee State Senator [[Randy Hultgren]] and Green Party nominee Daniel Kairis. Despite winning the endorsements from the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/editorials/ct-edit-congress-20101007,0,587673.story |title=For the US House |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date=2010-10-07 |access-date=2010-10-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009165815/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/editorials/ct-edit-congress-20101007,0,587673.story |archive-date=2010-10-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/elections/endorsements/2775994,CST-EDT-edit06a.article |title=Foster for 14th District |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=2010-10-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101012140615/http://www.suntimes.com/news/elections/endorsements/2775994%2CCST-EDT-edit06a.article |archivedate=October 12, 2010 }}</ref> and ''[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|The Daily Herald]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20101016/discuss/710179901/|title=Congress, 14th District: Foster |newspaper=[[Daily Herald (Arlington Heights)|The Daily Herald]] |date=2010-10-16 }}</ref> Foster lost to Hultgren 51%\u201345%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=489038|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 IL \u2013 District 14 Race \u2013 Nov 02, 2010 |work=ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://newsblogs.chicagotribune.com/clout_st/2010/11/debbie-halvorson-adam-kinzinger-dan-seals-robert-dold-bill-foster-randy-hultgren.html|title=Clout St. Democrat Foster concedes defeat in 14th District|date=2010-11-02 | work=Chicago Tribune}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{Main|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois#District 11}}\nIn May 2011, Foster sold his home in [[Geneva, Illinois|Geneva]], moved to [[Naperville, Illinois|Naperville]] and announced plans to run for Congress in the 11th District, which encompasses [[Aurora, Illinois|Aurora]], [[Joliet, Illinois|Joliet]], [[Lisle, Illinois|Lisle]] in addition to Naperville.  It also includes roughly a quarter of his old district.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2011/05/illinois_congress_2012_bill_fo_1.html |title=Illinois Congress 2012: Bill Foster running in new 11th district |author=Lynn Sweet |date=31 May 2011 |work=Chicago Sun Times |accessdate=1 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110602011613/http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2011/05/illinois_congress_2012_bill_fo_1.html |archivedate=2 June 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"chitribmay\">{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chibrknews-in-wake-of-remap-plan-exlawmaker-to-run-again-20110531,0,1494745.story |title=In wake of remap plan, ex-lawmaker to run again |author=Katherine Skiba |date=31 May 2011 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |publisher= |accessdate=1 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026090343/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chibrknews-in-wake-of-remap-plan-exlawmaker-to-run-again-20110531,0,1494745.story |archive-date=26 October 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  The district had previously been the 13th, represented by seven-term Republican [[Judy Biggert]].   Although Biggert's home in [[Hinsdale, Illinois|Hinsdale]] had been shifted to the Chicago-based 5th District, Biggert opted to seek election in the 11th, which contained half of her old territory.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mike Flannery|first=Dane Placko|title=FOX Chicago Sunday: Biggert, Foster debate to represent 11th Congressional District\n|work=Fox Chicago|date=Aug 9, 2012|url=http://www.myfoxchicago.com/story/19238594/judy-biggert-bill-foster-debate-cadidates-congressional-district-11-fox-chicago-sunday|url-status=dead\n|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121126094540/http://www.myfoxchicago.com/story/19238594/judy-biggert-bill-foster-debate-cadidates-congressional-district-11-fox-chicago-sunday\n|archivedate=2012-11-26}}</ref>\n\nOn November 6, 2012, Foster won the election for the 11th district with 58% of the vote; Biggert conceded the race at 9:45pm.<ref>{{cite news|last=Matt Hanley|first=Jenette Sturges|title=Foster returns to Congress with win over Biggert|work=The Herald-News|date=November 6, 2012|url=http://heraldnews.suntimes.com/news/elections/16065869-418/foster-returns-to-congress-with-win-over-biggert.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130203052511/http://heraldnews.suntimes.com/news/elections/16065869-418/foster-returns-to-congress-with-win-over-biggert.html|url-status=dead\n|archive-date=February 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{Main|2014 United States House of Representatives elections in Illinois#District 11}}\nFoster ran again and was unopposed in the Democratic primary in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.il.gov/Downloads/ElectionInformation/VoteTotals/2014GPOfficialVote.pdf|title=Official Illinois State Board of Elections Results \u2013 March 18, 2014 Primary Election (P. 31)|accessdate=December 28, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021140211/http://www.elections.il.gov/Downloads/ElectionInformation/VoteTotals/2014GPOfficialVote.pdf|archive-date=October 21, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> For the general election, he faced Republican nominee, State Representative [[Darlene Senger]], and defeated her with 53.5% of the vote to her 46.5% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionInformation/GetVoteTotals.aspx |title=Illinois General Election 2014|publisher=Illinois State Board of Elections|date=2014-11-04 |accessdate=2014-12-28}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nAlthough it was initially thought that Foster would not be sworn in until April due to the need to count absentee ballots before the first election would be certified, he took the oath of office on March 11.<ref name=\"hague_20080311\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyherald.com/story/?id=151577&src=5 |newspaper=Daily Herald |title=Foster sworn into Congress |date=2008-03-11 |accessdate=2008-03-12 |author=Hague, Leslie}}</ref>\n\nFoster joined [[Vern Ehlers]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]-[[Michigan|MI]]) and [[Rush D. Holt Jr.|Rush Holt Jr.]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[New Jersey|NJ]]) as the only [[physicist|research physicists]] ever to be elected to Congress.<ref>{{cite news|author=Cornelia Dean|title=Physicists in Congress Calculate Their Influence|date=2008-07-10|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/06/10/science/10phys.html|accessdate=2010-02-11 }}</ref>\nOn his first day in office, he cast the deciding vote to keep from [[Table (parliamentary)|tabling]] an ethics bill that would create an independent outside panel to investigate ethics complaints against House members.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2008/roll121.xml | title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 121 | date=2008-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/news/politics/blog/2008/03/first_day_swing_vote_for_new_r.html|title=First day, swing vote for new Rep. Bill Foster|author=Jim Tankersley|newspaper=[[Baltimore Sun]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080317122525/http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/news/politics/blog/2008/03/first_day_swing_vote_for_new_r.html|archivedate=2008-03-17}}</ref>\n\n;Fundraising\nAccording to the Center for Responsive Politics, Bill Foster received $637,050 from labor related political action committees during his runs for Congress. $180,000 of this money came from PACs linked to public sector unions. $110,000 of these donations came from PACs linked to industrial labor unions.\n\nAccording to the Federal Election Commission, [[Nancy Pelosi]] gave $4,000 to Bill Foster\u2019s 2012 campaign committee. PACs under the control of Pelosi have donated $10,000 to his 2012 campaign.\n\n;Taxes\n\nFoster supported allowing the [[Bush tax cuts]] to expire. During a debate with his opponent in the 2012 election Foster said, \u201cThe tax cuts were promised to generate job growth, but did not. If you follow the money, when you give a dollar to a very wealthy person, they won\u2019t typically put it back into the local economy.\u201d He said the tax benefits ended up in overseas accounts and spent on luxury purchases.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dauskurdas|first=Sherri|title=Biggert, Foster sit down for first debate of new 11th district|work=The Bugle|date=September 2, 2012|url=http://www.buglenewspapers.com/joliet/article_05bd8cd6-f51f-11e1-a3ff-001a4bcf6878.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120910050602/http://www.buglenewspapers.com/joliet/article_05bd8cd6-f51f-11e1-a3ff-001a4bcf6878.html|archivedate=2012-09-10}}</ref>\n\nBill Foster has opposed efforts to repeal the estate tax.  On 31 August 2005, U.S. Newswire reported that Foster said, \"The proponents of estate tax repeal are fond of calling it the \u2018death tax\u2019. It\u2019s not a death tax, it\u2019s a Rich Kids\u2019 tax.\" In 2009, just before the estate tax was scheduled for a one-year repeal, Foster voted to permanently extend the then current estate tax rate of 45%.\n\n;Card check\nAccording to the official Thomas website, Bill Foster co-sponsored the [[Employee Free Choice Act]] of 2009, which would enable unionization of small businesses of less that 50 employees. On 25 February 2012, the Daily Herald reported, \u201cFoster pointed to his support for the Employee Free Choice Act while serving at the congressman in the 14th District as proof of his union support.\"\n\n;Stimulus spending\nFoster voted for the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]]<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll046.xml</ref>\n\n;Health care reform\nFoster voted for the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], commonly referred to as Obamacare.<ref>{{cite web|title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 165|work=HR 3590 Recorded Vote : Bill Title: Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives|date=21 Mar 2010|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2010/roll165.xml}}</ref> On June 29, 2012, the ''Chicago Tribune'' reported that Foster said the following about his vote for Obamacare, \"I\u2019m proud of my vote, and I would be proud to do it again.\"\n\n;Dodd-Frank\nHe also voted for the [[Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act]], with all ten of the amendments he proposed being added to the final bill.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bill's Congressional Career|work=Billfoster.com|publisher=Bill Foster for Congress|url=http://www.billfoster.com/about/congress/|access-date=2012-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325065559/http://www.billfoster.com/about/congress/|archive-date=2012-03-25|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;Environment\nHe voted against the [[American Clean Energy and Security Act]], which would create a [[Cap and trade]] system.<ref>{{cite web|title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 477: HR 2454|work=Recorded Vote; Question: On Passage; Bill Title: American Clean Energy and Security Act|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives|date=26 Jun 2009|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2009/roll477.xml}}</ref>\n\n==== Second Amendment ====\nAsked if the Second Amendment should be up for reinterpretation, Foster said \u201cIt always has been up for reinterpretation. The technology changes, and the weapons thought to be too dangerous to be in private hands change. A civil war cannon is frankly much less dangerous than weapons we are allowed to carry on the streets in many of the states and cities in our country today. This is something where technology changes and public attitude changes and both are important in each of the generations.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/naperville-sun/ct-nvs-foster-gun-violence-forum-st-0404-20180403-story.html|title=Rep. Bill Foster: Second Amendment meant to be reinterpreted by each generation|last=Hegarty|first=Erin|website=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n;Committee assignments\n\n====Current====\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]]''' (2008\u20132011; 2013\u2013present)\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises|Subcommittee on Capital Markets and Government-Sponsored Enterprises]]\n**[[United States House Financial Services Subcommittee on Monetary Policy and Trade|Subcommittee on Monetary Policy and Trade]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space, & Technology]]'''\n**[[United States House Science Subcommittee on Environment|Subcommittee on Environment]]\n\n====Past====\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]''' (2008\u20132011)\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*'''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://newdemocratcoalition-himes.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|date=|accessdate=6 February 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|accessdate=13 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612140644/https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*'''[[U.S.-Japan Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://usjapancaucus-castro.house.gov/members|format=| publisher=U.S. - Japan Caucus |date=|accessdate=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Illinois 14th Congressional District Special Democratic Primary, 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionOperations/ElectionVoteTotals.aspx?ID=tqQnS5eHGWc%3d&OfficeType=%2brBqro%2b%2bHTUkQvv7Q1tDdQ%3d%3d|title=Election Results 2008 SPECIAL PRIMARY|accessdate=October 25, 2019|publisher=[[Illinois State Board of Elections]]}}</ref>