ter\n| votes = 12126\n| percentage = 58.48\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate = Juan Thomas\n| votes = 5212\n| percentage = 25.13\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate = Jim Hickey\n| votes = 3399\n| percentage = 16.39\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 20737\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Illinois 11th Congressional District General Election, 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionOperations/ElectionVoteTotals.aspx?ID=iX7bNPizmS8%3d&OfficeType=%2brBqro%2b%2bHTUkQvv7Q1tDdQ%3d%3d|title=Election Results 2012 GENERAL ELECTION|publisher=[[Illinois State Board of Elections]]|accessdate=October 25, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate = Bill Foster\n| votes = 148928\n| percentage = 58.57\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate = Judy Biggert ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 105348\n| percentage = 41.43\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n| party = Write-in votes\n| candidate = Chris Michel\n| votes = 19\n| percentage = 0.01\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 254295\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Illinois 11th Congressional District General Election, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionOperations/ElectionVoteTotals.aspx?ID=z%2fR%2feACUG%2bY%3d&OfficeType=%2brBqro%2b%2bHTUkQvv7Q1tDdQ%3d%3d|title=Election Results 2014 GENERAL ELECTION|publisher=[[Illinois State Board of Elections]]|accessdate=October 25, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate = Bill Foster ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 93436\n| percentage = 53.46\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate = [[Darlene Senger]]\n| votes = 81335\n| percentage = 46.54\n}}\n{{Election box candidate no change\n| party = Write-in votes\n| candidate = Constant \"Connor\" Vlakancic\n| votes = 1\n| percentage = 0.00\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 174772\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Illinois 11th Congressional District General Election, 2016<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionOperations/ElectionVoteTotals.aspx?ID=MdSiWa1xQus%3d&OfficeType=%2brBqro%2b%2bHTUkQvv7Q1tDdQ%3d%3d|title=Election Results 2016 GENERAL ELECTION|publisher=[[Illinois State Board of Elections]]|accessdate=October 25, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate = Bill Foster ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 166578\n| percentage = 60.45\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate = Tonia Khouri\n| votes = 108995\n| percentage = 39.55\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 275573\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Illinois 11th Congressional District General Election, 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.il.gov/ElectionOperations/ElectionVoteTotals.aspx?ID=JVM3BFfJbYc%3d&OfficeType=%2brBqro%2b%2bHTUkQvv7Q1tDdQ%3d%3d|title=Election Results 2018 GENERAL ELECTION|publisher=[[Illinois State Board of Elections]]|accessdate=October 25, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| candidate = Bill Foster ([[incumbent]])\n| votes = 145407\n| percentage = 63.84\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| candidate = Nick Stella\n| votes = 82358\n| percentage = 36.16\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 227765\n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nFoster and his wife, Aesook Byon, live in [[Naperville, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/sleuth/2009/01/three_house_members_wearing_ne.html |work=The Washington Post |title=Three House Members Wearing New Rings in the 111th}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://query.nictusa.com/cgi-bin/dcdev/forms/C00435099/746348/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120717042556/http://query.nictusa.com/cgi-bin/dcdev/forms/C00435099/746348/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-17 |title=Foster, Bill \u2013 Statement of Candidacy |publisher=Federal Elections Commission |date=2011-09-29 |accessdate=2011-10-04 }}</ref> He has two adult children from his first marriage.<ref name=\"chitribmay\" /> Foster has lived and worked in northern Illinois ([[Naperville, Illinois|Naperville]], [[Geneva, Illinois|Geneva]], [[Batavia, Illinois|Batavia]], and [[St. Charles, Illinois|St. Charles]]) since 1984.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130130221927/http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news%2Fpolitics&id=8846465 Biggert, Foster square off in 11th Dist. debate], [[ABC 7 Chicago]], October 13, 2012, complete video\n*[http://www.dailyherald.com/article/20120918/submitted/309189867/ 2012 candidate questionnaire] at the ''Daily Herald''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141020185327/http://elections.nwherald.com/candidate/63/ 2012 candidate questionnaire] at the ''Northwest Herald''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140202172054/http://www.suntimes.com/news/elections/questionnaires/2749584,14CDFoster.article 2012 candidate questionnaire] at the ''Chicago Sun-Times''\n*[http://chicagotonight.wttw.com/2012/02/23/bill-foster-q 2012 candidate questionnaire] at WTTW ''Chicago Tonight''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121123061249/http://abclocal.go.com/wls/feature?section=news%2Fpolitics%2Flocal_elections&id=8538936 2012 candidate questionnaire and video] at ABC 7 Chicago\n\n==External links==\n* [http://foster.house.gov/ Congressman Bill Foster] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.billfoster.com/ Bill Foster for Congress]\n*{{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Illinois/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Bill_Foster_%5BD-11%5D|Bill Foster}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=F000454 | votesmart=101632 | fec=H8IL14067 | congress=bill-foster/F000454 }}\n; Scientific\n* {{Worldcat id|np-foster,%20g%20william|G. William Foster}} academic papers\n* [http://research.ieeexplore.ieee.org/AuthorNetwork/AuthorSearchResult.jsp?authorid=43604771 IEEE \u2013 G. William Foster]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} academic journal papers\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state    = Illinois\n|district = 14\n|before   = [[Dennis Hastert]]\n|after    = [[Randy Hultgren]]\n|years    = 2008\u20132011}}\n|-\n{{US House succession box\n|state    = Illinois\n|district = 11\n|before   = [[Adam Kinzinger]]\n|years    = 2013\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Tim Walberg]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=148th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Justin Amash]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{IL-FedRep}}\n{{Current members of the U.S. House of Representatives}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foster, Bill}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Madison, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Illinois Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Madison, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Naperville, Illinois]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Raven Onthill", "label": "safe", "comment": "Switch the formatting of a title to match the rest of the article - whoops!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bill_Foster_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "Coherent Raman Scattering Microscopy", "text_new": "\n\n\n= '''Coherent Raman Scattering  Microscopy''' =\n[[File:Mouse ear XYZ green-lipid blue-protein.gif|thumb|Simultaneous two-color label-free stimulated Raman scattering z-stack imaging of mouse ear (red: protein, green: lipid, image is 220 by 220 microns the total depth is 60 microns, the pixel dwell time is 2 microsecond.)]]\n'''Coherent Raman scattering (CRS)''' microscopy is a [[multi-photon microscopy]] technique based on [[Raman scattering|Raman]] active vibrational modes of molecules. The two major techniques in CRS microscopy are stimulated Raman scattering (SRS) and [[Coherent anti-Stokes Raman spectroscopy|coherent anti-Stokes scattering (CARS)]]. SRS and CARS were theoretically predicted and experimental realized in the 1960s<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rigneault|first=Herv\u00e9|last2=Berto|first2=Pascal|date=2018-07-26|title=Tutorial: Coherent Raman light matter interaction processes|url=https://aip.scitation.org/doi/10.1063/1.5030335|journal=APL Photonics|volume=3|issue=9|pages=091101|doi=10.1063/1.5030335}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jones|first=W. J.|last2=Stoicheff|first2=B. P.|date=1964-11-30|title=Inverse Raman Spectra: Induced Absorption at Optical Frequencies|url=https://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRevLett.13.657|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=13|issue=22|pages=657\u2013659|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.13.657}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maker|first=P. D.|last2=Terhune|first2=R. W.|date=1965-02-01|title=Study of Optical Effects Due to an Induced Polarization Third Order in the Electric Field Strength|url=https://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRev.137.A801|journal=Physical Review|volume=137|issue=3A|pages=A801\u2013A818|doi=10.1103/PhysRev.137.A801}}</ref>. Not until 1982, was the first CARS microscopy demonstrated<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Manuccia|first=T. J.|last2=Reintjes|first2=J.|last3=Duncan|first3=M. D.|date=1982-08-01|title=Scanning coherent anti-Stokes Raman microscope|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-7-8-350|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=7|issue=8|pages=350\u2013352|doi=10.1364/OL.7.000350|issn=1539-4794}}</ref>. In 1999, a collinear geometry and high [[numerical aperture]] objective were used in CARS microscopy, which made the technique more compatible with modern [[Confocal microscopy|laser scanning microscope]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zumbusch|first=Andreas|last2=Holtom|first2=Gary R.|last3=Xie|first3=X. Sunney|date=1999-05-17|title=Three-Dimensional Vibrational Imaging by Coherent Anti-Stokes Raman Scattering|url=https://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRevLett.82.4142|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=82|issue=20|pages=4142\u20134145|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.82.4142}}</ref>. Since then, CRS's popularity in biomedical research started to grow. CRS is mainly used to image lipid, protein, and other bio-molecules in live or fixed cells or tissues without labeling or staining the sample<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1062325706|title=Coherent raman scattering microscopy|others=Cheng, Ji-Xin,, Xie, Xiaoliang Sunney,|isbn=978-1-138-19952-1|location=Boca Raton|oclc=1062325706}}</ref>. CRS can also be used to image samples labeled with Raman Tags<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />, which normally has higher CRS signal than common bio-molecules have. CRS also find applications in other fields like material science and environmental sciences.\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Principles energy levels.png|thumb|Energy diagrams of spontaneous and coherent Raman scatterings.]]\nCoherent Raman scattering is based on [[Raman scattering]] (or spontaneous Raman scattering). In spontaneous Raman, only one monochromatic excitation laser is used. Spontaneous Raman scattering's signal intensity grows linearly with the average power of a [[Continuous-wave laser|continuous wave pump laser]]. In CRS, two lasers are used to excite specific vibrational modes of molecules to be imaged.  The laser with a higher photon energy is normally called pump laser and the laser with a lower photon energy is called Stokes laser. Their photon energy differences match the energy of vibrational modes of molecules:\n\n<math>E_{Raman}=E_{pump}-E_{Stokes}</math>,\n\nwhere the <math>E_{Raman}=\\hbar \\Omega,\\ E_{pump}= \\hbar \\omega_{pump},\\ E_{Stokes}=\\hbar \\omega_{Stokes}</math>.\n\nCRS is a [[Nonlinear optics|nonlinear optical process]], where the signal level is normally multiplication of powers of pump and Stokes lasers. Therefore, most CRS microscopy experiments are performed with [[Pulsed laser|pulsed lasers]], where higher peak power improved the signal levels of CRS significantly.\n\n=== Coherent anti-Stokes Raman Scattering (CARS) Microscopy ===\n[[File:Forward and epi-detected CARS.tif|alt=|thumb|'''Forward and epi-detected CARS''']]\nIn CARS, photons generated in the anti-Stokes wavelength are being detected as signals.\n\n<math>E_{CARS}=E_{pump}+\\Omega=2\\times E_{pump}-E_{Stokes}</math>\n\nIn CARS microscopy, there are normally two ways to detect the newly generated photons. One is called forward-detected CARS, the other called epi-detected CARS<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=Ji-xin|last2=Volkmer|first2=Andreas|last3=Book|first3=Lewis D.|last4=Xie|first4=X. Sunney|date=2001|title=An Epi-Detected Coherent Anti-Stokes Raman Scattering (E-CARS) Microscope with High Spectral Resolution and High Sensitivity|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1021/jp003774a|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry B|volume=105|issue=7|pages=1277\u20131280|doi=10.1021/jp003774a|issn=1520-6106|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Volkmer|first=Andreas|last2=Cheng|first2=Ji-Xin|last3=Sunney Xie|first3=X.|date=2001-06-20|title=Vibrational Imaging with High Sensitivity via Epidetected Coherent Anti-Stokes Raman Scattering Microscopy|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1103/physrevlett.87.023901|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=87|issue=2|doi=10.1103/physrevlett.87.023901|issn=0031-9007}}</ref>. In forward-detected CARS, the generated CARS photons together with pump and Stokes lasers go through the samples. The pump and Stokes lasers are completely blocked by a high [[Optical Density|optical density]] (OD) filter. The CARS photons are then detected by a [[Photomultiplier tube|photonmultiplier tube]] (PMT)  or a camera. In epi-detected CARS, back scattered CARS photons are redirected by a [[Dichroic filter|dichroic mirror]] or [[Polarizing beam splitter|polarizing beam splitter.]] After high OD filters are used to block back scattered pump and Stokes lasers, the newly generated photons are detected by a PMT. The signal intensity of CARS has the following relationship with the pump and Stokes laser's intensity <math>I^2_{pump}, I_{Stokes}</math>, the number of molecules <math>N</math> in the focus of the lasers and the third order Raman susceptibility <math>\\chi ^{(3)} _{Raman}</math> of the molecule:\n\n<math>I_{CARS}\\propto (N \\chi ^{(3)} _{Raman})^2 I^2_{pump} I_{Stokes}</math>\n\nThe [[Signal-to-noise ratio (imaging)|signal-to-noise ratio]] (SNR), which is a more important characteristic in imaging experiments are square root of the number of CARS photons generated, which is also given below:\n\n<math>\nSNR_{CARS}\\propto N \\chi ^{(3)} _{Raman} I_{pump} \\sqrt{I_{Stokes}}</math>\n\nThere are other non-linear optical processes that also generate photons at the anti-Stokes wavelength. Those signals are normally called non-resonant (NR) four-wave-mixing (FWM) background in CARS microscopy. These background can [[Optical interference|interfere]] with the CARS signal either constructively or destructively<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Evans|first=Conor L.|last2=Xie|first2=X. Sunney|date=2008|title=Coherent Anti-Stokes Raman Scattering Microscopy: Chemical Imaging for Biology and Medicine|url=http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev.anchem.1.031207.112754|journal=Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry|language=en|volume=1|issue=1|pages=883\u2013909|doi=10.1146/annurev.anchem.1.031207.112754|issn=1936-1327|via=}}</ref>. However, the problem can be partially circumvented by subtracting the on- and off-resonance images<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xie|first=X. Sunney|last2=Saar|first2=Brian G.|last3=Evans|first3=Conor L.|last4=Ganikhanov|first4=Feruz|date=2006-06-15|title=High-sensitivity vibrational imaging with frequency modulation coherent anti-Stokes Raman scattering (FM CARS) microscopy|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-31-12-1872|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=31|issue=12|pages=1872\u20131874|doi=10.1364/OL.31.001872|issn=1539-4794}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xu|first=Chris|last2=Xia|first2=Yuanqin|last3=Xia|first3=Fei|last4=Li|first4=Bo|last5=Qin|first5=Yifan|date=2018-12-24|title=Multi-color background-free coherent anti-Stokes Raman scattering microscopy using a time-lens source|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/oe/abstract.cfm?uri=oe-26-26-34474|journal=Optics Express|language=EN|volume=26|issue=26|pages=34474\u201334483|doi=10.1364/OE.26.034474|issn=1094-4087|pmc=PMC6410910|pmid=30650870}}</ref> or using mathematical methods to retrieve the background free images<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Potma|first=Eric O.|last2=Alfonso Garcia|first2=Alba|date=2016-06-28|editor-last=Goda|editor-first=Keisuke|editor2-last=Tsia|editor2-first=Kevin K.|title=Mapping biological tissues with hyperspectral coherent Raman scattering microscopy (Conference Presentation)|url=https://spiedigitallibrary.org/conference-proceedings-of-spie/9720/2213565/Mapping-biological-tissues-with-hyperspectral-coherent-Raman-scattering-microscopyConference-Presentation/10.1117/12.2213565.full|journal=High-Speed Biomedical Imaging and Spectroscopy: Toward Big Data Instrumentation and Management|location=San Francisco, United States|publisher=SPIE|pages=14|doi=10.1117/12.2213565|isbn=9781628419542}}</ref>.\n\n=== Stimulated Raman Scattering (SRS) Microscopy  ===\nIn SRS, the energy transfer from pump laser to Stokes laser is measured as its signal. There are two ways to measure SRS signals, one is to measure the increase of power in Stokes laser, which is called stimulated Raman gain (SRG). The other is to measure the decrease of power in the pump laser, which is called stimulated Raman loss (SRL). Since the change of power is on the order of <math>10^{-3}</math> to <math>10^{-6}</math> compared with the original power of pump and Stokes lasers, a modulation transfer scheme<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fu|first=Dan|last2=Ye|first2=Tong|last3=Matthews|first3=Thomas E.|last4=Yurtsever|first4=Gunay|last5=Warren|first5=Warren S.|date=2007|title=Two-color, two-photon, and excited-state absorption microscopy|url=http://biomedicaloptics.spiedigitallibrary.org/article.aspx?doi=10.1117/1.2780173|journal=Journal of Biomedical Optics|language=en|volume=12|issue=5|pages=054004|doi=10.1117/1.2780173}}</ref> is normally employed to extract the SRS signals<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Freudiger|first=Christian W.|last2=Min|first2=Wei|last3=Saar|first3=Brian G.|last4=Lu|first4=Sijia|last5=Holtom|first5=Gary R.|last6=He|first6=Chengwei|last7=Tsai|first7=Jason C.|last8=Kang|first8=Jing X.|last9=Xie|first9=X. Sunney|date=2008-12-19|title=Label-Free Biomedical Imaging with High Sensitivity by Stimulated Raman Scattering Microscopy|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/lookup/doi/10.1126/science.1165758|journal=Science|language=en|volume=322|issue=5909|pages=1857\u20131861|doi=10.1126/science.1165758|issn=0036-8075|pmc=PMC3576036|pmid=19095943}}</ref>. The SRS signal depend on pump and Stokes power in the following way: \n\n<math>I_{SRS}\\propto N\\chi^{(3)}_{Raman} I_{pump}I_{Stokes}</math>\n\nShot-noise limited detection can be achieved if electronic noises from detectors are reduced well below optical noises. In shot-noise limited case, the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) of SRS is \n\n<math>SNR_{SRL}\\propto N\\chi^{(3)}_{Raman} \\sqrt{I_{pump}}I_{Stokes}</math>\n\n<math>SNR_{SRG}\\propto N\\chi^{(3)}_{Raman} I_{pump}\\sqrt{I_{Stokes}}</math>\n\nThe signal of SRS is free from non-resonant background existed in CARS microscopy, though much smaller non-resonant background from other optical process (e.g. [[cross-phase modulation]], multi-color multi-photon absorption) may exist.\n\nSRS can be detected in the forward direction and epi direction. In the forward-detected SRS, the modulated laser is blocked by high optical density filter and the other laser is measured by a photodiode. Modulation transferred from the modulated laser to the originally unmodulated laser is normally extracted by a lock-in amplifier from the output of photodiode. In epi-detected SRS, there are normally two methods to detect the SRS signal. One method is to detect the back scattered light in front of the objective by a photodiode with a hole at center. The other method is similar to the epi-detected CARS microscopy, where the back-scattered light went through the objective and deflected to the side of the light path normally with a combination of a polarizing beam splitter and a quarter wave-plate. The Stokes (or pump) laser was then detected after filtering out the pump (or Stokes laser). \n\n=== Two-color, multi-color, and hyper-spectral CRS microscopy ===\nImaging samples at different wave-numbers can provide a more specific and quantitative chemical mapping of the sample<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kong|first=Lingjie|last2=Ji|first2=Minbiao|last3=Holtom|first3=Gary R.|last4=Fu|first4=Dan|last5=Freudiger|first5=Christian W.|last6=Xie|first6=X. Sunney|date=2013-01-15|title=Multicolor stimulated Raman scattering microscopy with a rapidly tunable optical parametric oscillator|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-38-2-145|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=38|issue=2|pages=145\u2013147|doi=10.1364/OL.38.000145|issn=1539-4794|pmc=PMC3588591|pmid=23454943}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lu|first=Fa-Ke|last2=Ji|first2=Minbiao|last3=Fu|first3=Dan|last4=Ni|first4=Xiaohui|last5=Freudiger|first5=Christian W.|last6=Holtom|first6=Gary|last7=Xie|first7=X. Sunney|date=2012-08-10|title=Multicolor stimulated Raman scattering microscopy|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/00268976.2012.695028|journal=Molecular Physics|volume=110|issue=15-16|pages=1927\u20131932|doi=10.1080/00268976.2012.695028|issn=0026-8976|pmc=PMC3596086|pmid=23504195}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Young Jong|last2=Liu|first2=Yuexin|last3=Cicerone|first3=Marcus T.|date=2007-11-15|title=Characterization of three-color CARS in a two-pulse broadband CARS spectrum|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-32-22-3370|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=32|issue=22|pages=3370\u20133372|doi=10.1364/OL.32.003370|issn=1539-4794}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ozeki|first=Yasuyuki|last2=Umemura|first2=Wataru|last3=Sumimura|first3=Kazuhiko|last4=Nishizawa|first4=Norihiko|last5=Fukui|first5=Kiichi|last6=Itoh|first6=Kazuyoshi|date=2012-02-01|title=Stimulated Raman hyperspectral imaging based on spectral filtering of broadband fiber laser pulses|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-37-3-431|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=37|issue=3|pages=431\u2013433|doi=10.1364/OL.37.000431|issn=1539-4794}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Ke|last2=Zhang|first2=Delong|last3=Charan|first3=Kriti|last4=Slipchenko|first4=Mikhail N.|last5=Wang|first5=Ping|last6=Xu|first6=Chris|last7=Cheng|first7=Ji-Xin|date=2013|title=Time-lens based hyperspectral stimulated Raman scattering imaging and quantitative spectral analysis|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/jbio.201300005|journal=Journal of Biophotonics|language=en|volume=6|issue=10|pages=815\u2013820|doi=10.1002/jbio.201300005|issn=1864-0648|pmc=PMC3899243|pmid=23840041}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Liao|first=Chien-Sheng|last2=Slipchenko|first2=Mikhail N|last3=Wang|first3=Ping|last4=Li|first4=Junjie|last5=Lee|first5=Seung-Young|last6=Oglesbee|first6=Robert A|last7=Cheng|first7=Ji-Xin|date=2015|title=Microsecond scale vibrational spectroscopic imaging by multiplex stimulated Raman scattering microscopy|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/lsa201538|journal=Light: Science & Applications|language=en|volume=4|issue=3|pages=e265\u2013e265|doi=10.1038/lsa.2015.38|issn=2047-7538|pmc=PMC4498251|pmid=26167336|via=}}</ref>. This can be achieved by image at different wavenumbers one after another. This operation always involves some type of tuning: tuning of laser's wavelength, tuning of spectral filtering device, or tuning of time delay between pump and Stokes lasers in the case of spectral-focusing CRS. Another way of doing multi-color CRS is to use one picosecond laser with a narrow spectral bandwidth (<1 nm) as pump or Stokes and the other laser with broad spectral bandwidth as Stokes or pump laser. In this case, the spectrum of transmitted broadband laser can be spread by a grating and measured by an array of detectors.  \n\n=== Spectral-focusing CRS ===\nCRS normally use lasers with narrow bandwidth lasers, whose bandwidth < 1 nm, to maintain good spectral resolution ~ 15 cm<sup>-1</sup>. Lasers with sub 1 nm bandwidth are picosecond lasers. In spectral-focusing CRS, femtosecond pump and Stokes lasers are equally linearly chirped into picosecond lasers<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hellerer|first=Thomas|last2=Enejder|first2=Annika M.K.|last3=Zumbusch|first3=Andreas|date=2004-06-29|title=Spectral focusing: High spectral resolution spectroscopy with broad-bandwidth laser pulses|url=https://aip.scitation.org/doi/10.1063/1.1768312|journal=Applied Physics Letters|volume=85|issue=1|pages=25\u201327|doi=10.1063/1.1768312|issn=0003-6951}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Andresen|first=Esben Ravn|last2=Berto|first2=Pascal|last3=Rigneault|first3=Herv\u00e9|date=2011-07-01|title=Stimulated Raman scattering microscopy by spectral focusing and fiber-generated soliton as Stokes pulse|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-36-13-2387|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=36|issue=13|pages=2387\u20132389|doi=10.1364/OL.36.002387|issn=1539-4794}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fu|first=Dan|last2=Holtom|first2=Gary|last3=Freudiger|first3=Christian|last4=Zhang|first4=Xu|last5=Xie|first5=Xiaoliang Sunney|date=2013-04-25|title=Hyperspectral Imaging with Stimulated Raman Scattering by Chirped Femtosecond Lasers|url=https://doi.org/10.1021/jp308938t|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry B|volume=117|issue=16|pages=4634\u20134640|doi=10.1021/jp308938t|issn=1520-6106|pmc=PMC3637845|pmid=23256635}}</ref>. The effective bandwidth become smaller and therefore, high spectral-resolution can be achieved this way with femtosecond lasers. The wavenumber tuning of spectral-focusing CRS can be achieved both by changing the center wavelength of lasers and by changing the delay between pump and Stokes lasers. <br />\n== Applications ==\n\n=== Coherent Raman Histology ===\nOne of the major applications for CRS is label-free histology, which is also called coherent Raman histology, or sometimes stimulated Raman histology<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Evans|first=Conor L.|last2=Xu|first2=Xiaoyin|last3=Kesari|first3=Santosh|last4=Xie|first4=X. Sunney|last5=Wong|first5=Stephen T. C.|last6=Young|first6=Geoffrey S.|date=2007-09-17|title=Chemically-selective imaging of brain structures with CARS microscopy|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/oe/abstract.cfm?uri=oe-15-19-12076|journal=Optics Express|language=EN|volume=15|issue=19|pages=12076\u201312087|doi=10.1364/OE.15.012076|issn=1094-4087}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinigel|first=M|last2=Breunig|first2=H G|last3=Kellner-H\u00f6fer|first3=M|last4=B\u00fcckle|first4=R|last5=Darvin|first5=M E|last6=Klemp|first6=M|last7=Lademann|first7=J|last8=K\u00f6nig|first8=K|date=2014-05-01|title=In vivo histology: optical biopsies with chemical contrast using clinical multiphoton/coherent anti-Stokes Raman scattering tomography|url=http://stacks.iop.org/1612-202X/11/i=5/a=055601?key=crossref.62713a1868be6e2507c4acc9e176e742|journal=Laser Physics Letters|volume=11|issue=5|pages=055601|doi=10.1088/1612-2011/11/5/055601|issn=1612-2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ji|first=M.|last2=Orringer|first2=D. A.|last3=Freudiger|first3=C. W.|last4=Ramkissoon|first4=S.|last5=Liu|first5=X.|last6=Lau|first6=D.|last7=Golby|first7=A. J.|last8=Norton|first8=I.|last9=Hayashi|first9=M.|last10=Agar|first10=N. Y. R.|last11=Young|first11=G. S.|date=2013-09-04|title=Rapid, Label-Free Detection of Brain Tumors with Stimulated Raman Scattering Microscopy|url=http://stm.sciencemag.org/cgi/doi/10.1126/scitranslmed.3005954|journal=Science Translational Medicine|language=en|volume=5|issue=201|pages=201ra119\u2013201ra119|doi=10.1126/scitranslmed.3005954|issn=1946-6234|pmc=PMC3806096|pmid=24005159}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Orringer|first=Daniel A.|last2=Pandian|first2=Balaji|last3=Niknafs|first3=Yashar S.|last4=Hollon|first4=Todd C.|last5=Boyle|first5=Julianne|last6=Lewis|first6=Spencer|last7=Garrard|first7=Mia|last8=Hervey-Jumper|first8=Shawn L.|last9=Garton|first9=Hugh J. L.|last10=Maher|first10=Cormac O.|last11=Heth|first11=Jason A.|date=2017|title=Rapid intraoperative histology of unprocessed surgical specimens via fibre-laser-based stimulated Raman scattering microscopy|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/s41551-016-0027|journal=Nature Biomedical Engineering|language=en|volume=1|issue=2|pages=0027|doi=10.1038/s41551-016-0027|issn=2157-846X|pmc=PMC5612414|pmid=28955599|via=}}</ref>. In CRH, CRS images are obtained at lipid and protein images and after some image processing, a image similar to H&E staining can be obtained. Different from H&E staining, CRH can be done on live and fresh tissue and doesn't need fixation and staining.\n\n=== Cell Metabolism ===\nThe metabolism of small molecules like glucose<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Long|first=Rong|last2=Zhang|first2=Luyuan|last3=Shi|first3=Lingyan|last4=Shen|first4=Yihui|last5=Hu|first5=Fanghao|last6=Zeng|first6=Chen|last7=Min|first7=Wei|date=2018|title=Two-color vibrational imaging of glucose metabolism using stimulated Raman scattering|url=http://xlink.rsc.org/?DOI=C7CC08217G|journal=Chemical Communications|language=en|volume=54|issue=2|pages=152\u2013155|doi=10.1039/C7CC08217G|issn=1359-7345|pmc=PMC5764084|pmid=29218356}}</ref>, cholesterol<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Hyeon Jeong|last2=Zhang|first2=Wandi|last3=Zhang|first3=Delong|last4=Yang|first4=Yang|last5=Liu|first5=Bin|last6=Barker|first6=Eric L.|last7=Buhman|first7=Kimberly K.|last8=Slipchenko|first8=Lyudmila V.|last9=Dai|first9=Mingji|last10=Cheng|first10=Ji-Xin|date=2015|title=Assessing Cholesterol Storage in Live Cells and C. elegans by Stimulated Raman Scattering Imaging of Phenyl-Diyne Cholesterol|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/srep07930|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=5|issue=1|pages=7930|doi=10.1038/srep07930|issn=2045-2322|pmc=PMC4302291|pmid=25608867|via=}}</ref>, and drugs<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Fu|first=Dan|last2=Zhou|first2=Jing|last3=Zhu|first3=Wenjing Suzanne|last4=Manley|first4=Paul W.|last5=Wang|first5=Y. Karen|last6=Hood|first6=Tami|last7=Wylie|first7=Andrew|last8=Xie|first8=X. Sunney|date=2014|title=Imaging the intracellular distribution of tyrosine kinase inhibitors in living cells with quantitative hyperspectral stimulated Raman scattering|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/nchem.1961|journal=Nature Chemistry|language=en|volume=6|issue=7|pages=614\u2013622|doi=10.1038/nchem.1961|issn=1755-4330|pmc=PMC4205760|pmid=24950332|via=}}</ref> are studied with CRS in live cells. CRS provide a way to measure molecular distribution and quantities with relatively high throughput.\n\n=== Myelin Imaging ===\nMyelin is rich in lipid. CRS is routinely used to image myelin in live or fixed tissues to study [[Neurodegenerative Disease|neurodegenerative diseases]] or other neural disorders<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Haifeng|last2=Fu|first2=Yan|last3=Zickmund|first3=Phyllis|last4=Shi|first4=Riyi|last5=Cheng|first5=Ji-Xin|date=2005-07-01|title=Coherent Anti-Stokes Raman Scattering Imaging of Axonal Myelin in Live Spinal Tissues|url=https://www.cell.com/biophysj/abstract/S0006-3495(05)72706-5|journal=Biophysical Journal|language=English|volume=89|issue=1|pages=581\u2013591|doi=10.1529/biophysj.105.061911|issn=0006-3495|pmc=PMC1366558|pmid=15834003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Belanger|first=Erik|last2=Cr\u00e9peau|first2=Jo\u00ebl|last3=Laffray|first3=Sophie|last4=Vall\u00e9e|first4=R\u00e9al|last5=Koninck|first5=Yves De|last6=C\u00f4t\u00e9|first6=Daniel|date=2012|title=Live animal myelin histomorphometry of the spinal cord with video-rate multimodal nonlinear microendoscopy|url=https://www.spiedigitallibrary.org/journals/Journal-of-Biomedical-Optics/volume-17/issue-2/021107/Live-animal-myelin-histomorphometry-of-the-spinal-cord-with-video/10.1117/1.JBO.17.2.021107.short|journal=Journal of Biomedical Optics|volume=17|issue=2|pages=021107|doi=10.1117/1.JBO.17.2.021107|issn=1083-3668|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tian|first=Feng|last2=Yang|first2=Wenlong|last3=Mordes|first3=Daniel A.|last4=Wang|first4=Jin-Yuan|last5=Salameh|first5=Johnny S.|last6=Mok|first6=Joanie|last7=Chew|first7=Jeannie|last8=Sharma|first8=Aarti|last9=Leno-Duran|first9=Ester|last10=Suzuki-Uematsu|first10=Satomi|last11=Suzuki|first11=Naoki|date=2016|title=Monitoring peripheral nerve degeneration in ALS by label-free stimulated Raman scattering imaging|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms13283|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=13283|doi=10.1038/ncomms13283|issn=2041-1723|pmc=PMC5095598|pmid=27796305|via=}}</ref>. \n\n=== Pharmaceutical Research ===\nThe functions of drugs can be studied by CRS too. For example, an anti-leukemia drug [[imatinib]] are studied with SRS in leukemia cell lines<ref name=\":0\" />. The study revealed the possible mechanism of its metabolism in cells and provided insight about ways to improve drug effectiveness.\n\n=== Raman Tags ===\nEven though CRS allows label-free imaging, Raman tags can also be used to boost signal for specific targets<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Holtom|first=Gary R.|last2=Thrall|first2=Brian D.|last3=Chin|first3=Beek-Yoke|last4=Wiley|first4=H. Steven|last5=Colson|first5=Steven D.|date=2001|title=Achieving Molecular Selectivity in Imaging Using Multiphoton Raman Spectroscopy Techniques|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1034/j.1600-0854.2001.21106.x|journal=Traffic|language=en|volume=2|issue=11|pages=781\u2013788|doi=10.1034/j.1600-0854.2001.21106.x|issn=1600-0854}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Wei|first=Lu|last2=Hu|first2=Fanghao|last3=Shen|first3=Yihui|last4=Chen|first4=Zhixing|last5=Yu|first5=Yong|last6=Lin|first6=Chih-Chun|last7=Wang|first7=Meng C|last8=Min|first8=Wei|date=2014|title=Live-cell imaging of alkyne-tagged small biomolecules by stimulated Raman scattering|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/nmeth.2878|journal=Nature Methods|language=en|volume=11|issue=4|pages=410\u2013412|doi=10.1038/nmeth.2878|issn=1548-7091|pmc=PMC4040164|pmid=24584195|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Hong|first=Senlian|last2=Chen|first2=Tao|last3=Zhu|first3=Yuntao|last4=Li|first4=Ang|last5=Huang|first5=Yanyi|last6=Chen|first6=Xing|date=2014|title=Live-Cell Stimulated Raman Scattering Imaging of Alkyne-Tagged Biomolecules|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/anie.201400328|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|language=en|volume=53|issue=23|pages=5827\u20135831|doi=10.1002/anie.201400328|issn=1521-3773}}</ref>. For example, deuterated molecules are used to shift Raman signal to a band where the interference from other molecules is absent. Specially engineered molecules containing isotopes can be used as Raman tags to achieve super-multiplexing multi-color imaging with SRS<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Wei|first=Lu|last2=Chen|first2=Zhixing|last3=Shi|first3=Lixue|last4=Long|first4=Rong|last5=Anzalone|first5=Andrew V.|last6=Zhang|first6=Luyuan|last7=Hu|first7=Fanghao|last8=Yuste|first8=Rafael|last9=Cornish|first9=Virginia W.|last10=Min|first10=Wei|date=2017|title=Super-multiplex vibrational imaging|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/nature22051|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=544|issue=7651|pages=465\u2013470|doi=10.1038/nature22051|issn=0028-0836|pmc=PMC5939925|pmid=28424513|via=}}</ref>.\n\n== Comparison to confocal Raman microscopy ==\nConfocal Raman microscopy provides a broad spectrum for each pixel in the images. It takes a long time to scan the whole sample, since each pixel requires seconds for data acquisition. So the whole imaging process is long and therefore, it is more suitable for samples that do not move. CRS on the other hand measures signals at single wavenumber but allow fast scanning. If more spectral information is needed, multi-color or hyperspectral CRS can be used and the scanning speed or data quality will be compromised accordingly.\n\n== Comparison between SRS and CARS ==\nIn CRS microscopy, we can regard SRS and CARS as two aspects of the same process. Therefore, they normally provide similar sensitivities, which is normally measured by signal-to-noise ratios (SNR). Their differences are mainly in detection methods. In CARS microscopy, PMT, APD or cameras are used as detectors to detect photons generated in the CARS process. PMT is most commonly used due to its large detection area and high speed. In SRS microscopy, photodiodes are normally used to measure the laser beams, which is higher in power. Because of such differences, the application of CARS and SRS are also different.  \n\nPMT normally has relatively low [[quantum efficiency]] compared with photodiodes. This will negatively impact the SNR of CARS microscopy. PMT's also has reduced sensitivity for lasers with wavelength longer than 650 nm. Therefore, with the commonly used laser system for CRS, CARS is mainly used to image at high wavenumber region <math>(2800\\ cm^{-1}\\sim3400\\ cm^{-1})</math>. The SNR of CARS microscopy is normally poor for finger-print imaging <math>(400\\ cm^{-1}\\sim1800\\ cm^{-1})</math>.  \n\nSRS microscopy mainly use [[Photodiode|silicon photodiode]] as detectors. Si photoidoes have much higher quantum efficiency than PMT, that is one of the reasons that the SNR of SRS can be slightly better than CARS in many cases. Si Photodiodes also suffer reduced sensitivity when the wavelength of laser is longer than 850 nm. However, the sensitivity is still relatively high and allow for imaging in fingerprint region <math>(400\\ cm^{-1}\\sim1800\\ cm^{-1})</math>.    \n\n== See Also ==\n[[Raman scattering]]\n\n[[Raman spectroscopy]]\n\n[[Coherent anti-Stokes Raman spectroscopy|CARS spectroscopy]]\n\n== References ==<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n", "text_old": "\n\n\n= '''Coherent Raman Scattering  Microscopy''' =\n[[File:Mouse ear XYZ green-lipid blue-protein.gif|thumb|Simultaneous two-color label-free stimulated Raman scattering z-stack imaging of mouse ear (red: protein, green: lipid, image is 220 by 220 microns the total depth is 60 microns, the pixel dwell time is 2 microsecond.)]]\n'''Coherent Raman scattering (CRS)''' microscopy is a [[multi-photon microscopy]] technique based on [[Raman scattering|Raman]] active vibrational modes of molecules. The two major techniques in CRS microscopy are stimulated Raman scattering (SRS) and [[Coherent anti-Stokes Raman spectroscopy|coherent anti-Stokes scattering (CARS)]]. SRS and CARS were theoretically predicted and experimental realized in the 1960s<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rigneault|first=Herv\u00e9|last2=Berto|first2=Pascal|date=2018-07-26|title=Tutorial: Coherent Raman light matter interaction processes|url=https://aip.scitation.org/doi/10.1063/1.5030335|journal=APL Photonics|volume=3|issue=9|pages=091101|doi=10.1063/1.5030335}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jones|first=W. J.|last2=Stoicheff|first2=B. P.|date=1964-11-30|title=Inverse Raman Spectra: Induced Absorption at Optical Frequencies|url=https://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRevLett.13.657|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=13|issue=22|pages=657\u2013659|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.13.657}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maker|first=P. D.|last2=Terhune|first2=R. W.|date=1965-02-01|title=Study of Optical Effects Due to an Induced Polarization Third Order in the Electric Field Strength|url=https://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRev.137.A801|journal=Physical Review|volume=137|issue=3A|pages=A801\u2013A818|doi=10.1103/PhysRev.137.A801}}</ref>. Not until 1982, was the first CARS microscopy demonstrated<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Manuccia|first=T. J.|last2=Reintjes|first2=J.|last3=Duncan|first3=M. D.|date=1982-08-01|title=Scanning coherent anti-Stokes Raman microscope|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-7-8-350|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=7|issue=8|pages=350\u2013352|doi=10.1364/OL.7.000350|issn=1539-4794}}</ref>. In 1999, a collinear geometry and high [[numerical aperture]] objective were used in CARS microscopy, which made the technique more compatible with modern [[Confocal microscopy|laser scanning microscope]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zumbusch|first=Andreas|last2=Holtom|first2=Gary R.|last3=Xie|first3=X. Sunney|date=1999-05-17|title=Three-Dimensional Vibrational Imaging by Coherent Anti-Stokes Raman Scattering|url=https://link.aps.org/doi/10.1103/PhysRevLett.82.4142|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=82|issue=20|pages=4142\u20134145|doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.82.4142}}</ref>. Since then, CRS's popularity in biomedical research started to grow. CRS is mainly used to image lipid, protein, and other bio-molecules in live or fixed cells or tissues without labeling or staining the sample<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1062325706|title=Coherent raman scattering microscopy|others=Cheng, Ji-Xin,, Xie, Xiaoliang Sunney,|isbn=978-1-138-19952-1|location=Boca Raton|oclc=1062325706}}</ref>. CRS can also be used to image samples labeled with Raman Tags<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />, which normally has higher CRS signal than common bio-molecules have. CRS also find applications in other fields like material science and environmental sciences.\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Principles energy levels.png|thumb|Energy diagrams of spontaneous and coherent Raman scatterings.]]\nCoherent Raman scattering is based on [[Raman scattering]] (or spontaneous Raman scattering). In spontaneous Raman, only one monochromatic excitation laser is used. Spontaneous Raman scattering's signal intensity grows linearly with the average power of a [[Continuous-wave laser|continuous wave pump laser]]. In CRS, two lasers are used to excite specific vibrational modes of molecules to be imaged.  The laser with a higher photon energy is normally called pump laser and the laser with a lower photon energy is called Stokes laser. Their photon energy differences match the energy of vibrational modes of molecules:\n\n<math>E_{Raman}=E_{pump}-E_{Stokes}</math>,\n\nwhere the <math>E_{Raman}=\\hbar \\Omega,\\ E_{pump}= \\hbar \\omega_{pump},\\ E_{Stokes}=\\hbar \\omega_{Stokes}</math>.\n\nCRS is a [[Nonlinear optics|nonlinear optical process]], where the signal level is normally multiplication of powers of pump and Stokes lasers. Therefore, most CRS microscopy experiments are performed with [[Pulsed laser|pulsed lasers]], where higher peak power improved the signal levels of CRS significantly.\n\n=== Coherent anti-Stokes Raman Scattering (CARS) Microscopy ===\n[[File:Forward and epi-detected CARS.tif|alt=|thumb|'''Forward and epi-detected CARS''']]\nIn CARS, photons generated in the anti-Stokes wavelength are being detected as signals.\n\n<math>E_{CARS}=E_{pump}+\\Omega=2\\times E_{pump}-E_{Stokes}</math>\n\nIn CARS microscopy, there are normally two ways to detect the newly generated photons. One is called forward-detected CARS, the other called epi-detected CARS<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cheng|first=Ji-xin|last2=Volkmer|first2=Andreas|last3=Book|first3=Lewis D.|last4=Xie|first4=X. Sunney|date=2001|title=An Epi-Detected Coherent Anti-Stokes Raman Scattering (E-CARS) Microscope with High Spectral Resolution and High Sensitivity|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1021/jp003774a|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry B|volume=105|issue=7|pages=1277\u20131280|doi=10.1021/jp003774a|issn=1520-6106|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Volkmer|first=Andreas|last2=Cheng|first2=Ji-Xin|last3=Sunney Xie|first3=X.|date=2001-06-20|title=Vibrational Imaging with High Sensitivity via Epidetected Coherent Anti-Stokes Raman Scattering Microscopy|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1103/physrevlett.87.023901|journal=Physical Review Letters|volume=87|issue=2|doi=10.1103/physrevlett.87.023901|issn=0031-9007}}</ref>. In forward-detected CARS, the generated CARS photons together with pump and Stokes lasers go through the samples. The pump and Stokes lasers are completely blocked by a high [[Optical Density|optical density]] (OD) filter. The CARS photons are then detected by a [[Photomultiplier tube|photonmultiplier tube]] (PMT)  or a camera. In epi-detected CARS, back scattered CARS photons are redirected by a [[Dichroic filter|dichroic mirror]] or [[Polarizing beam splitter|polarizing beam splitter.]] After high OD filters are used to block back scattered pump and Stokes lasers, the newly generated photons are detected by a PMT. The signal intensity of CARS has the following relationship with the pump and Stokes laser's intensity <math>I^2_{pump}, I_{Stokes}</math>, the number of molecules <math>N</math> in the focus of the lasers and the third order Raman susceptibility <math>\\chi ^{(3)} _{Raman}</math> of the molecule:\n\n<math>I_{CARS}\\propto (N \\chi ^{(3)} _{Raman})^2 I^2_{pump} I_{Stokes}</math>\n\nThe [[Signal-to-noise ratio (imaging)|signal-to-noise ratio]] (SNR), which is a more important characteristic in imaging experiments are square root of the number of CARS photons generated, which is also given below:\n\n<math>\nSNR_{CARS}\\propto N \\chi ^{(3)} _{Raman} I_{pump} \\sqrt{I_{Stokes}}</math>\n\nThere are other non-linear optical processes that also generate photons at the anti-Stokes wavelength. Those signals are normally called non-resonant (NR) four-wave-mixing (FWM) background in CARS microscopy. These background can [[Optical interference|interfere]] with the CARS signal either constructively or destructively<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Evans|first=Conor L.|last2=Xie|first2=X. Sunney|date=2008|title=Coherent Anti-Stokes Raman Scattering Microscopy: Chemical Imaging for Biology and Medicine|url=http://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev.anchem.1.031207.112754|journal=Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry|language=en|volume=1|issue=1|pages=883\u2013909|doi=10.1146/annurev.anchem.1.031207.112754|issn=1936-1327|via=}}</ref>. However, the problem can be partially circumvented by subtracting the on- and off-resonance images<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xie|first=X. Sunney|last2=Saar|first2=Brian G.|last3=Evans|first3=Conor L.|last4=Ganikhanov|first4=Feruz|date=2006-06-15|title=High-sensitivity vibrational imaging with frequency modulation coherent anti-Stokes Raman scattering (FM CARS) microscopy|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-31-12-1872|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=31|issue=12|pages=1872\u20131874|doi=10.1364/OL.31.001872|issn=1539-4794}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Xu|first=Chris|last2=Xia|first2=Yuanqin|last3=Xia|first3=Fei|last4=Li|first4=Bo|last5=Qin|first5=Yifan|date=2018-12-24|title=Multi-color background-free coherent anti-Stokes Raman scattering microscopy using a time-lens source|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/oe/abstract.cfm?uri=oe-26-26-34474|journal=Optics Express|language=EN|volume=26|issue=26|pages=34474\u201334483|doi=10.1364/OE.26.034474|issn=1094-4087|pmc=PMC6410910|pmid=30650870}}</ref> or using mathematical methods to retrieve the background free images<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Potma|first=Eric O.|last2=Alfonso Garcia|first2=Alba|date=2016-06-28|editor-last=Goda|editor-first=Keisuke|editor2-last=Tsia|editor2-first=Kevin K.|title=Mapping biological tissues with hyperspectral coherent Raman scattering microscopy (Conference Presentation)|url=https://spiedigitallibrary.org/conference-proceedings-of-spie/9720/2213565/Mapping-biological-tissues-with-hyperspectral-coherent-Raman-scattering-microscopyConference-Presentation/10.1117/12.2213565.full|journal=High-Speed Biomedical Imaging and Spectroscopy: Toward Big Data Instrumentation and Management|location=San Francisco, United States|publisher=SPIE|pages=14|doi=10.1117/12.2213565|isbn=9781628419542}}</ref>.\n\n=== Stimulated Raman Scattering (SRS) Microscopy  ===\nIn SRS, the energy transfer from pump laser to Stokes laser is measured as its signal. There are two ways to measure SRS signals, one is to measure the increase of power in Stokes laser, which is called stimulated Raman gain (SRG). The other is to measure the decrease of power in the pump laser, which is called stimulated Raman loss (SRL). Since the change of power is on the order of <math>10^{-3}</math> to <math>10^{-6}</math> compared with the original power of pump and Stokes lasers, a modulation transfer scheme<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fu|first=Dan|last2=Ye|first2=Tong|last3=Matthews|first3=Thomas E.|last4=Yurtsever|first4=Gunay|last5=Warren|first5=Warren S.|date=2007|title=Two-color, two-photon, and excited-state absorption microscopy|url=http://biomedicaloptics.spiedigitallibrary.org/article.aspx?doi=10.1117/1.2780173|journal=Journal of Biomedical Optics|language=en|volume=12|issue=5|pages=054004|doi=10.1117/1.2780173}}</ref> is normally employed to extract the SRS signals<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Freudiger|first=Christian W.|last2=Min|first2=Wei|last3=Saar|first3=Brian G.|last4=Lu|first4=Sijia|last5=Holtom|first5=Gary R.|last6=He|first6=Chengwei|last7=Tsai|first7=Jason C.|last8=Kang|first8=Jing X.|last9=Xie|first9=X. Sunney|date=2008-12-19|title=Label-Free Biomedical Imaging with High Sensitivity by Stimulated Raman Scattering Microscopy|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/lookup/doi/10.1126/science.1165758|journal=Science|language=en|volume=322|issue=5909|pages=1857\u20131861|doi=10.1126/science.1165758|issn=0036-8075|pmc=PMC3576036|pmid=19095943}}</ref>. The SRS signal depend on pump and Stokes power in the following way: \n\n<math>I_{SRS}\\propto N\\chi^{(3)}_{Raman} I_{pump}I_{Stokes}</math>\n\nShot-noise limited detection can be achieved if electronic noises from detectors are reduced well below optical noises. In shot-noise limited case, the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) of SRS is \n\n<math>SNR_{SRL}\\propto N\\chi^{(3)}_{Raman} \\sqrt{I_{pump}}I_{Stokes}</math>\n\n<math>SNR_{SRG}\\propto N\\chi^{(3)}_{Raman} I_{pump}\\sqrt{I_{Stokes}}</math>\n\nThe signal of SRS is free from non-resonant background existed in CARS microscopy, though much smaller non-resonant background from other optical process (e.g. [[cross-phase modulation]], multi-color multi-photon absorption) may exist.\n\nSRS can be detected in the forward direction and epi direction. In the forward-detected SRS, the modulated laser is blocked by high optical density filter and the other laser is measured by a photodiode. Modulation transferred from the modulated laser to the originally unmodulated laser is normally extracted by a lock-in amplifier from the output of photodiode. In epi-detected SRS, there are normally two methods to detect the SRS signal. One method is to detect the back scattered light in front of the objective by a photodiode with a hole at center. The other method is similar to the epi-detected CARS microscopy, where the back-scattered light went through the objective and deflected to the side of the light path normally with a combination of a polarizing beam splitter and a quarter wave-plate. The Stokes (or pump) laser was then detected after filtering out the pump (or Stokes laser). \n\n=== Two-color, multi-color, and hyper-spectral CRS microscopy ===\nImaging samples at different wave-numbers can provide a more specific and quantitative chemical mapping of the sample<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kong|first=Lingjie|last2=Ji|first2=Minbiao|last3=Holtom|first3=Gary R.|last4=Fu|first4=Dan|last5=Freudiger|first5=Christian W.|last6=Xie|first6=X. Sunney|date=2013-01-15|title=Multicolor stimulated Raman scattering microscopy with a rapidly tunable optical parametric oscillator|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-38-2-145|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=38|issue=2|pages=145\u2013147|doi=10.1364/OL.38.000145|issn=1539-4794|pmc=PMC3588591|pmid=23454943}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lu|first=Fa-Ke|last2=Ji|first2=Minbiao|last3=Fu|first3=Dan|last4=Ni|first4=Xiaohui|last5=Freudiger|first5=Christian W.|last6=Holtom|first6=Gary|last7=Xie|first7=X. Sunney|date=2012-08-10|title=Multicolor stimulated Raman scattering microscopy|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/00268976.2012.695028|journal=Molecular Physics|volume=110|issue=15-16|pages=1927\u20131932|doi=10.1080/00268976.2012.695028|issn=0026-8976|pmc=PMC3596086|pmid=23504195}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Young Jong|last2=Liu|first2=Yuexin|last3=Cicerone|first3=Marcus T.|date=2007-11-15|title=Characterization of three-color CARS in a two-pulse broadband CARS spectrum|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-32-22-3370|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=32|issue=22|pages=3370\u20133372|doi=10.1364/OL.32.003370|issn=1539-4794}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ozeki|first=Yasuyuki|last2=Umemura|first2=Wataru|last3=Sumimura|first3=Kazuhiko|last4=Nishizawa|first4=Norihiko|last5=Fukui|first5=Kiichi|last6=Itoh|first6=Kazuyoshi|date=2012-02-01|title=Stimulated Raman hyperspectral imaging based on spectral filtering of broadband fiber laser pulses|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-37-3-431|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=37|issue=3|pages=431\u2013433|doi=10.1364/OL.37.000431|issn=1539-4794}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Ke|last2=Zhang|first2=Delong|last3=Charan|first3=Kriti|last4=Slipchenko|first4=Mikhail N.|last5=Wang|first5=Ping|last6=Xu|first6=Chris|last7=Cheng|first7=Ji-Xin|date=2013|title=Time-lens based hyperspectral stimulated Raman scattering imaging and quantitative spectral analysis|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/jbio.201300005|journal=Journal of Biophotonics|language=en|volume=6|issue=10|pages=815\u2013820|doi=10.1002/jbio.201300005|issn=1864-0648|pmc=PMC3899243|pmid=23840041}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Liao|first=Chien-Sheng|last2=Slipchenko|first2=Mikhail N|last3=Wang|first3=Ping|last4=Li|first4=Junjie|last5=Lee|first5=Seung-Young|last6=Oglesbee|first6=Robert A|last7=Cheng|first7=Ji-Xin|date=2015|title=Microsecond scale vibrational spectroscopic imaging by multiplex stimulated Raman scattering microscopy|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/lsa201538|journal=Light: Science & Applications|language=en|volume=4|issue=3|pages=e265\u2013e265|doi=10.1038/lsa.2015.38|issn=2047-7538|pmc=PMC4498251|pmid=26167336|via=}}</ref>. This can be achieved by image at different wavenumbers one after another. This operation always involves some type of tuning: tuning of laser's wavelength, tuning of spectral filtering device, or tuning of time delay between pump and Stokes lasers in the case of spectral-focusing CRS. Another way of doing multi-color CRS is to use one picosecond laser with a narrow spectral bandwidth (<1 nm) as pump or Stokes and the other laser with broad spectral bandwidth as Stokes or pump laser. In this case, the spectrum of transmitted broadband laser can be spread by a grating and measured by an array of detectors.  \n\n=== Spectral-focusing CRS ===\nCRS normally use lasers with narrow bandwidth lasers, whose bandwidth < 1 nm, to maintain good spectral resolution ~ 15 cm<sup>-1</sup>. Lasers with sub 1 nm bandwidth are picosecond lasers. In spectral-focusing CRS, femtosecond pump and Stokes lasers are equally linearly chirped into picosecond lasers<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hellerer|first=Thomas|last2=Enejder|first2=Annika M.K.|last3=Zumbusch|first3=Andreas|date=2004-06-29|title=Spectral focusing: High spectral resolution spectroscopy with broad-bandwidth laser pulses|url=https://aip.scitation.org/doi/10.1063/1.1768312|journal=Applied Physics Letters|volume=85|issue=1|pages=25\u201327|doi=10.1063/1.1768312|issn=0003-6951}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Andresen|first=Esben Ravn|last2=Berto|first2=Pascal|last3=Rigneault|first3=Herv\u00e9|date=2011-07-01|title=Stimulated Raman scattering microscopy by spectral focusing and fiber-generated soliton as Stokes pulse|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/ol/abstract.cfm?uri=ol-36-13-2387|journal=Optics Letters|language=EN|volume=36|issue=13|pages=2387\u20132389|doi=10.1364/OL.36.002387|issn=1539-4794}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Fu|first=Dan|last2=Holtom|first2=Gary|last3=Freudiger|first3=Christian|last4=Zhang|first4=Xu|last5=Xie|first5=Xiaoliang Sunney|date=2013-04-25|title=Hyperspectral Imaging with Stimulated Raman Scattering by Chirped Femtosecond Lasers|url=https://doi.org/10.1021/jp308938t|journal=The Journal of Physical Chemistry B|volume=117|issue=16|pages=4634\u20134640|doi=10.1021/jp308938t|issn=1520-6106|pmc=PMC3637845|pmid=23256635}}</ref>. The effective bandwidth become smaller and therefore, high spectral-resolution can be achieved this way with femtosecond lasers. The wavenumber tuning of spectral-focusing CRS can be achieved both by changing the center wavelength of lasers and by changing the delay between pump and Stokes lasers. <br />\n== Applications ==\n\n=== Coherent Raman Histology ===\nOne of the major applications for CRS is label-free histology, which is also called coherent Raman histology, or sometimes stimulated Raman histology<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Evans|first=Conor L.|last2=Xu|first2=Xiaoyin|last3=Kesari|first3=Santosh|last4=Xie|first4=X. Sunney|last5=Wong|first5=Stephen T. C.|last6=Young|first6=Geoffrey S.|date=2007-09-17|title=Chemically-selective imaging of brain structures with CARS microscopy|url=https://www.osapublishing.org/oe/abstract.cfm?uri=oe-15-19-12076|journal=Optics Express|language=EN|volume=15|issue=19|pages=12076\u201312087|doi=10.1364/OE.15.012076|issn=1094-4087}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Weinigel|first=M|last2=Breunig|first2=H G|last3=Kellner-H\u00f6fer|first3=M|last4=B\u00fcckle|first4=R|last5=Darvin|first5=M E|last6=Klemp|first6=M|last7=Lademann|first7=J|last8=K\u00f6nig|first8=K|date=2014-05-01|title=In vivo histology: optical biopsies with chemical contrast using clinical multiphoton/coherent anti-Stokes Raman scattering tomography|url=http://stacks.iop.org/1612-202X/11/i=5/a=055601?key=crossref.62713a1868be6e2507c4acc9e176e742|journal=Laser Physics Letters|volume=11|issue=5|pages=055601|doi=10.1088/1612-2011/11/5/055601|issn=1612-2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ji|first=M.|last2=Orringer|first2=D. A.|last3=Freudiger|first3=C. W.|last4=Ramkissoon|first4=S.|last5=Liu|first5=X.|last6=Lau|first6=D.|last7=Golby|first7=A. J.|last8=Norton|first8=I.|last9=Hayashi|first9=M.|last10=Agar|first10=N. Y. R.|last11=Young|first11=G. S.|date=2013-09-04|title=Rapid, Label-Free Detection of Brain Tumors with Stimulated Raman Scattering Microscopy|url=http://stm.sciencemag.org/cgi/doi/10.1126/scitranslmed.3005954|journal=Science Translational Medicine|language=en|volume=5|issue=201|pages=201ra119\u2013201ra119|doi=10.1126/scitranslmed.3005954|issn=1946-6234|pmc=PMC3806096|pmid=24005159}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Orringer|first=Daniel A.|last2=Pandian|first2=Balaji|last3=Niknafs|first3=Yashar S.|last4=Hollon|first4=Todd C.|last5=Boyle|first5=Julianne|last6=Lewis|first6=Spencer|last7=Garrard|first7=Mia|last8=Hervey-Jumper|first8=Shawn L.|last9=Garton|first9=Hugh J. L.|last10=Maher|first10=Cormac O.|last11=Heth|first11=Jason A.|date=2017|title=Rapid intraoperative histology of unprocessed surgical specimens via fibre-laser-based stimulated Raman scattering microscopy|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/s41551-016-0027|journal=Nature Biomedical Engineering|language=en|volume=1|issue=2|pages=0027|doi=10.1038/s41551-016-0027|issn=2157-846X|pmc=PMC5612414|pmid=28955599|via=}}</ref>. In CRH, CRS images are obtained at lipid and protein images and after some image processing, a image similar to H&E staining can be obtained. Different from H&E staining, CRH can be done on live and fresh tissue and doesn't need fixation and staining.\n\n=== Cell Metabolism ===\nThe metabolism of small molecules like glucose<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Long|first=Rong|last2=Zhang|first2=Luyuan|last3=Shi|first3=Lingyan|last4=Shen|first4=Yihui|last5=Hu|first5=Fanghao|last6=Zeng|first6=Chen|last7=Min|first7=Wei|date=2018|title=Two-color vibrational imaging of glucose metabolism using stimulated Raman scattering|url=http://xlink.rsc.org/?DOI=C7CC08217G|journal=Chemical Communications|language=en|volume=54|issue=2|pages=152\u2013155|doi=10.1039/C7CC08217G|issn=1359-7345|pmc=PMC5764084|pmid=29218356}}</ref>, cholesterol<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Hyeon Jeong|last2=Zhang|first2=Wandi|last3=Zhang|first3=Delong|last4=Yang|first4=Yang|last5=Liu|first5=Bin|last6=Barker|first6=Eric L.|last7=Buhman|first7=Kimberly K.|last8=Slipchenko|first8=Lyudmila V.|last9=Dai|first9=Mingji|last10=Cheng|first10=Ji-Xin|date=2015|title=Assessing Cholesterol Storage in Live Cells and C. elegans by Stimulated Raman Scattering Imaging of Phenyl-Diyne Cholesterol|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/srep07930|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=5|issue=1|pages=7930|doi=10.1038/srep07930|issn=2045-2322|pmc=PMC4302291|pmid=25608867|via=}}</ref>, and drugs<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Fu|first=Dan|last2=Zhou|first2=Jing|last3=Zhu|first3=Wenjing Suzanne|last4=Manley|first4=Paul W.|last5=Wang|first5=Y. Karen|last6=Hood|first6=Tami|last7=Wylie|first7=Andrew|last8=Xie|first8=X. Sunney|date=2014|title=Imaging the intracellular distribution of tyrosine kinase inhibitors in living cells with quantitative hyperspectral stimulated Raman scattering|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/nchem.1961|journal=Nature Chemistry|language=en|volume=6|issue=7|pages=614\u2013622|doi=10.1038/nchem.1961|issn=1755-4330|pmc=PMC4205760|pmid=24950332|via=}}</ref> are studied with CRS in live cells. CRS provide a way to measure molecular distribution and quantities with relatively high throughput.\n\n=== Myelin Imaging ===\nMyelin is rich in lipid. CRS is routinely used to image myelin in live or fixed tissues to study [[Neurodegenerative Disease|neurodegenerative diseases]] or other neural disorders<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Haifeng|last2=Fu|first2=Yan|last3=Zickmund|first3=Phyllis|last4=Shi|first4=Riyi|last5=Cheng|first5=Ji-Xin|date=2005-07-01|title=Coherent Anti-Stokes Raman Scattering Imaging of Axonal Myelin in Live Spinal Tissues|url=https://www.cell.com/biophysj/abstract/S0006-3495(05)72706-5|journal=Biophysical Journal|language=English|volume=89|issue=1|pages=581\u2013591|doi=10.1529/biophysj.105.061911|issn=0006-3495|pmc=PMC1366558|pmid=15834003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Belanger|first=Erik|last2=Cr\u00e9peau|first2=Jo\u00ebl|last3=Laffray|first3=Sophie|last4=Vall\u00e9e|first4=R\u00e9al|last5=Koninck|first5=Yves De|last6=C\u00f4t\u00e9|first6=Daniel|date=2012|title=Live animal myelin histomorphometry of the spinal cord with video-rate multimodal nonlinear microendoscopy|url=https://www.spiedigitallibrary.org/journals/Journal-of-Biomedical-Optics/volume-17/issue-2/021107/Live-animal-myelin-histomorphometry-of-the-spinal-cord-with-video/10.1117/1.JBO.17.2.021107.short|journal=Journal of Biomedical Optics|volume=17|issue=2|pages=021107|doi=10.1117/1.JBO.17.2.021107|issn=1083-3668|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tian|first=Feng|last2=Yang|first2=Wenlong|last3=Mordes|first3=Daniel A.|last4=Wang|first4=Jin-Yuan|last5=Salameh|first5=Johnny S.|last6=Mok|first6=Joanie|last7=Chew|first7=Jeannie|last8=Sharma|first8=Aarti|last9=Leno-Duran|first9=Ester|last10=Suzuki-Uematsu|first10=Satomi|last11=Suzuki|first11=Naoki|date=2016|title=Monitoring peripheral nerve degeneration in ALS by label-free stimulated Raman scattering imaging|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/ncomms13283|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=7|issue=1|pages=13283|doi=10.1038/ncomms13283|issn=2041-1723|pmc=PMC5095598|pmid=27796305|via=}}</ref>. \n\n=== Pharmaceutical Research ===\nThe functions of drugs can be studied by CRS too. For example, an anti-leukemia drug [[imatinib]] are studied with SRS in leukemia cell lines<ref name=\":0\" />. The study revealed the possible mechanism of its metabolism in cells and provided insight about ways to improve drug effectiveness.\n\n=== Raman Tags ===\nEven though CRS allows label-free imaging, Raman tags can also be used to boost signal for specific targets<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Holtom|first=Gary R.|last2=Thrall|first2=Brian D.|last3=Chin|first3=Beek-Yoke|last4=Wiley|first4=H. Steven|last5=Colson|first5=Steven D.|date=2001|title=Achieving Molecular Selectivity in Imaging Using Multiphoton Raman Spectroscopy Techniques|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1034/j.1600-0854.2001.21106.x|journal=Traffic|language=en|volume=2|issue=11|pages=781\u2013788|doi=10.1034/j.1600-0854.2001.21106.x|issn=1600-0854}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Wei|first=Lu|last2=Hu|first2=Fanghao|last3=Shen|first3=Yihui|last4=Chen|first4=Zhixing|last5=Yu|first5=Yong|last6=Lin|first6=Chih-Chun|last7=Wang|first7=Meng C|last8=Min|first8=Wei|date=2014|title=Live-cell imaging of alkyne-tagged small biomolecules by stimulated Raman scattering|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/nmeth.2878|journal=Nature Methods|language=en|volume=11|issue=4|pages=410\u2013412|doi=10.1038/nmeth.2878|issn=1548-7091|pmc=PMC4040164|pmid=24584195|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Hong|first=Senlian|last2=Chen|first2=Tao|last3=Zhu|first3=Yuntao|last4=Li|first4=Ang|last5=Huang|first5=Yanyi|last6=Chen|first6=Xing|date=2014|title=Live-Cell Stimulated Raman Scattering Imaging of Alkyne-Tagged Biomolecules|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/anie.201400328|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|language=en|volume=53|issue=23|pages=5827\u20135831|doi=10.1002/anie.201400328|issn=1521-3773}}</ref>. For example, deuterated molecules are used to shift Raman signal to a band where the interference from other molecules is absent. Specially engineered molecules containing isotopes can be used as Raman tags to achieve super-multiplexing multi-color imaging with SRS<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Wei|first=Lu|last2=Chen|first2=Zhixing|last3=Shi|first3=Lixue|last4=Long|first4=Rong|last5=Anzalone|first5=Andrew V.|last6=Zhang|first6=Luyuan|last7=Hu|first7=Fanghao|last8=Yuste|first8=Rafael|last9=Cornish|first9=Virginia W.|last10=Min|first10=Wei|date=2017|title=Super-multiplex vibrational imaging|url=http://www.nature.com/articles/nature22051|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=544|issue=7651|pages=465\u2013470|doi=10.1038/nature22051|issn=0028-0836|pmc=PMC5939925|pmid=28424513|via=}}</ref>.\n\n== Comparison to confocal Raman microscopy ==\nConfocal Raman microscopy provides a broad spectrum for each pixel in the images. It takes a long time to scan the whole sample, since each pixel requires seconds for data acquisition. So the whole imaging process is long and therefore, it is more suitable for samples that do not move. CRS on the other hand measures signals at single wavenumber but allow fast scanning. If more spectral information is needed, multi-color or hyperspectral CRS can be used and the scanning speed or data quality will be compromised accordingly.\n\n== Comparison between SRS and CARS ==\nIn CRS microscopy, we can regard SRS and CARS as two aspects of the same process. Therefore, they normally provide similar sensitivities, which is normally measured by signal-to-noise ratios (SNR). Their differences are mainly in detection methods. In CARS microscopy, PMT, APD or cameras are used as detectors to detect photons generated in the CARS process. PMT is most commonly used due to its large detection area and high speed. In SRS microscopy, photodiodes are normally used to measure the laser beams, which is higher in power. Because of such differences, the application of CARS and SRS are also different.  \n\nPMT normally has relatively low [[quantum efficiency]] compared with photodiodes. This will negatively impact the SNR of CARS microscopy. PMT's also has reduced sensitivity for lasers with wavelength longer than 650 nm. Therefore, with the commonly used laser system for CRS, CARS is mainly used to image at high wavenumber region <math>(2800\\ cm^{-1}\\sim3400\\ cm^{-1})</math>. The SNR of CARS microscopy is normally poor for finger-print imaging <math>(400\\ cm^{-1}\\sim1800\\ cm^{-1})</math>.  \n\nSRS microscopy mainly use [[Photodiode|silicon photodiode]] as detectors. Si photoidoes have much higher quantum efficiency than PMT, that is one of the reasons that the SNR of SRS can be slightly better than CARS in many cases. Si Photodiodes also suffer reduced sensitivity when the wavelength of laser is longer than 850 nm. However, the sensitivity is still relatively high and allow for imaging in fingerprint region <math>(400\\ cm^{-1}\\sim1800\\ cm^{-1})</math>.    \n\n== See Also ==\n[[Raman scattering]]\n\n[[Raman spectroscopy]]\n\n[[Coherent anti-Stokes Raman spectroscopy|CARS spectroscopy]]\n\n{{tl|AFC submission|t||ts=20190717202416|u=YangWenlong|ns=2|demo=}}<!-- Important, do not remove this line before article has been created. -->\n\n== References ==<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n", "name_user": "YangWenlong", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee Also:removed \"AFC submission\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coherent_Raman_Scattering_Microscopy"}
{"title_page": "Old North Church (Sierra Madre, California)", "text_new": "{{About| Old North Church in Sierra Madre, California, for Boston see:||Old North Church|Boston}}\n{{Infobox Historic building\n|name=Old North Church <br/>Christ Church Sierra Madre - ''Sierra Madre Congregational Church'' \n|image=Old_North_Church,_Sierra_Madre,_California.jpg\n|caption=Old North Church, Sierra Madre, California, a historic landmark.\n|location_town=[[Sierra Madre, California]]\n|location_country=[[United States]]\n| designations        = Sierra Madre Historic Landmark #40\n|architect=\n|construction_start_date= April 1890\n|completion_date= Dec. 14, 1890\n|date_demolished=\n|cost=$3,300\n| altitude            = {{convert|263|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n|structural_system= Wood\n| status              = Used for Youth Groups<br/> and Indonesia Church: Jemaat Kristen\n| current_tenants = Christ Church Sierra Madre, formerly called ''Sierra Madre Congregational Church''\n|style=[[Georgian architecture]]\n| map_type            = Los Angeles\n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = Old North Church in Sierra Madre, California\n| coordinates    = {{coord|34.1622306|-118.0566944|region:US-PA_type:landmark|display=inline}}\n| website = https://www.christchurchsm.org\n}}\n\n[[Image:Sierra Madre Congregational Church 1928.jpg|right|thumb|250px|'''Christ Church Sierra Madre - Sierra Madre Congregational Church''', a historic landmark <br/>Sierra Madre Historic Landmark #44 <br/> Architect: Marsh, Smith, & Powell <BR/> Construction started: 1925 <br/> Construction completion: 1928<BR/> Total Cost: $80,000 <br/>*Pritchard Hall and Admin building $40,000<br/>*Sanctuary $35,000<br/>*Furniture $5,000<br/>Architectural style: Romanesque Revival<BR/>Across the Street from Old North Church]]\n\n[[File:Old-North-Church-Sierra-Madre-California-1890.jpg|thumb|right|Old North Church in Sierra Madre at completion in 1890]]\n\n[[Image:Original Sierra Madre City Library.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Original 1887 Sierra Madre City Library on Central Ave, renamed Sierra Madre Blvd in 1936. Sierra Madre Congregational Church temporary meeting place in 1889.]]\n\n[[Image:Sierra Madre Town Hall 1895.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Original 1895 Sierra Madre Town Hall (with Cigar Factory next door) at Baldwin and Central Ave (now a gas station) . Sierra Madre Congregational Church temporary meeting place.]]\n\n[[Image:Central Ave Sierra Madre CA 1904-Old North Church .jpg|right|thumb|250px|Central Ave, Sierra Madre CA in 1905. A mule team is grading the Ave for the installation of the 1906 Pacific Electric street car, in the background is the Old North Church with the original barn roof bell tower.]]\n\n[[File:OldNorthChurchSierraMadreCalifornia1909.jpg|thumb|right|Old North Church Sierra Madre California 1909]]\n\n[[Image:Sierra_Madre_Memorial_Park_-_SM_Blvd_and_Hermosa.jpg|thumb|right|[[Sierra Madre Memorial Park]] at Sierra Madre Blvd and Hermosa looking North. From foreground to back ground: Weeping Wall Veterans Memorial, Sierra Madre Veterans Time Capsule bench, 1905 World War I Cannon,  Sierra Madre Boulevard, The Old North Church and the [[San Gabriel Mountains]]]].\n\n[[File:OldNorthChurchSierra_MadreCalifornia1906.jpg|thumb|right|Old North Church in 1906, looking North on Hermosa Ave]]\n\n'''Old North Church''' (ONC) is in [[Sierra Madre, California]].\nOld North Church is a [[Historic site|historic landmark]] building built in 1890, one of the oldest [[Church (building)|church]]es and buildings in Sierra Madre. The Old North Church is owned by it builder '''Sierra Madre Congregational Church''', called '''First Congregational Church of Sierra Madre''' at the time of completion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.geoview.info/old_north_church,5379055|title=Old North Church church, California, United States|author=|date=|website=us.geoview.info|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> It is site #45 on Sierra Madre designated historical landmarks list. There are forty-eight properties listed on Sierra Madre's Designated Historical Properties List.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofsierramadre.com/services/planning_and_building/historic_preservation|title=Historic Preservation - Sierra Madre|author=|date=|website=www.cityofsierramadre.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/historic-properties.html|title=Sierra Madre:  Historic Properties|author=|date=|website=www.smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> In September of 2018 Sierra Madre Congregational Church changed its name to '''Christ Church Sierra Madre'''.<ref>[https://www.christchurchsm.org/ Christ Church Sierra Madre, official web site]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Old North Church was constructed by hand with local wood. It is located on the north side of the current [[Sierra Madre Blvd]] at Hermosa. In 1890 Sierra Madre Blvd was a dirt street called Central Avenue. Old North Church is currently owned by its builder, Sierra Madre Congregational Church. The Old North Church is closely linked with the early settlement of Sierra Madre.<ref name=\"smccnet\">{{cite web|url=http://christchurchsm.org/about/|title=christchurchsm.org/about/, Sierra Madre Congregational Church-(SMCC), Church History, EARLY YEARS|author=|date=|website=smccnet.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>  The community of Sierra Madre was established in the fall of 1881. Sierra Madre Congregational Church started as a [[Sunday School]] class in February 1882. Without a building of its own, the church originally met in the city's original 1882 [[one-room school]]house at the corner of Hermosa and Live Oak, now called [[Orange Grove Boulevard (Pasadena)|Orange Grove]]. To use the schoolhouse as a church on Sunday mornings, the [[pump organ]], [[Hymnal|hymnbooks]], and winter [[firewood]] were transported to the schoolhouse by the attendees. The following years the Church met in the original [[City Hall]] at the corner Baldwin and Central Ave (Sierra Madre), then the original city [[library]] (1889), located at the current library site.  With the completion of the Old North Church in 1890, the church had its own meeting spot. Congregational Church of Sierra Madre was officially established on March 27, 1886 as a [[nondenominational church]] [[congregational church]], with 13 founding members, called ''First Congregational Church of Sierra Madre'' then. One of the 13 founding members was Mrs. Annetta M. Carter, wife of the city founder Nathaniel Coburn Carter. From 1908 to 1910 the Old North Church was expanded with the addition of new meeting rooms.<ref name=\"smccnet\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/histprop/191.pdf|title=Sierra Madre Historical Preservation Society, Old North Church|author=|date=|website=smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/photo-gallery.html|title=Photo Gallery|author=|date=|website=www.smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Church's second, and current, main building was built across the street. Construction of the new building started in 1926 with Pritchard Hall and was completed in 1928 with the new sanctuary dedicated on June 17, 1928. The sanctuary cornerstone was laid on Feb. 19, 1928.<ref name=\"smccnet\" /> The 1928 Church building is also a Sierra Madre designated historical landmark, as site #39. Having outgrown the Old North Church in the mid 1920s, the Congregational Church of Sierra Madre built a new stone Church in a [[Romanesque Revival architecture]] style, designed by Marsh, Smith, & Powell.<ref name=\"smcctimeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofsierramadre.com/services/library/local_history/sierra_madre_timeline/|title=Sierra Madre Historical Timeline - Sierra Madre|author=|date=|website=www.cityofsierramadre.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> Later after the move, the Old North Church was rented to the First [[Church of the Nazarene]] in 1939, then purchased by them in 1942. After the Church of the Nazarene outgrew the Old North Church, it was sold back to Sierra Madre Congregational Church in 1976.<ref>City of Sierra Madre, General Plan Technical Background Report, September 2012, PDF file, cityofsierramadre.com/documents</ref> Congregational Church purchased back the Old North Church for the use of its youth and children, its current role.  Sierra Madre's [[Cub Scout#United States|Cub Scouts]] Pack 373, and some of [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scouts]] Troop 373, meetings are held in the Old North Church. Troop 373 was founded in the Old North Church in 1924. [[Cub Scout#United States|Cub Scouts]] Pack 373 was started in 1971. Troop 373 was one of the founders of the Sierra Madre [[Fourth of July]] [[parade]] that then ran from historic [[Sierra Madre Memorial Park]] (across the street from the ONC) to historic [[Sierra Madre Pioneer Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierramadretroop373.org|title=Pack 373 Dens|first=|last=Pack 373|date=|website=Pack373|accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierramadretroop373.org|title=Boy Scouts Troop 373|first=|last=Troop 373|date=|website=Troop373|accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Old North Church survived the [[1991 Sierra Madre earthquake]] relatively undamaged. The 1928 building had damage to the [[bell tower]], which was torn down brick by brick and rebuilt.  The original ONC bell tower was built with a [[barn]] shaped roof, modeled after a Dutch church in Holland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/photo-gallery.html|title=Photo Gallery|author=|date=|website=www.smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> Later the Church of the Nazarene changed the bell tower to have a more classic pointed [[spire]]. The bell tower housed the 1893 bell weighing 517 pounds, in 1928 the bell was moved to the new south bell tower.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s-media-cache-ak0.pinimg.com/736x/b8/68/4d/b8684dc5cc8bd15109129e84dd54b002--sierra-gabriel.jpg|title=Old North Church Barn roof|author=|date=|website=pinimg.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>Independent Star-News from Pasadena, California, Page 72, February 15, 1959</ref>\n\nIn 1890 Old North Church attendees had to walk, ride a horse or ride in a horse buggy. In January 1906 the [[Pacific Electric]] street car was installed and rolled in front of the Old North Church, on the [[Sierra Madre (Pacific Electric)|Sierra Madre line]], each day from January 1, 1906 till service ended on October 6, 1950.<ref name=\"smcctimeline\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erha.org/pelines/pensm.htm|title=Pacific Electric Sierra Madre Line|author=|date=|website=www.erha.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nMrs. Annetta M. Carter (Feb, 10, 1846-Sept. 24, 1937), wife of Nathaniel Coburn Carter (Jan. 24, 1840 - Sept. 2, 1904), was key founder of Sierra Madre Congregational Church.<ref name=\"smccnet\" />Nathaniel and Annetta married in Feb. of 1864 and had 5 children: Florence, (now Mrs. William H. Mead); Arthur N. (b1868), Julia F., Anita E. (the first child born in the Sierra Madre, (b1883, m1910 to Holt R Gregory) and Phillip C (b1885). Annetta M. Pierce (Carter) and Nathaniel both were natives of [[Lowell, Massachusetts]], Nathaniel came to California for his health in 1871.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Nathaniel-Carter/6000000033555250826|title=Nathaniel Coburn Carter|author=|date=|website=geni_family_tree|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1996-01-23/local/me-27784_1_sierra-madre LA Times, Community Profile: Sierra Madre, January 23, 1996, by CECILIA RASMUSSEN]</ref><ref>Annual Publication of the Historical Society of Southern California, Volume 6, Page 178, In memory of Nathaniel Coburn Carter</ref> In February 1881, Nathaniel Carter purchased the original 1103 acres that comprised the new city of Sierra Madre. The land was acquired in three purchases: 845 acres of [[Rancho Santa Anita]] from [[Lucky Baldwin]], 108 acres from the [[Southern Pacific Railroad Company]] and 150 acres from John Richardson (1811-Aug. 9, 1884).<ref>[http://www.smhps.org/archivedpdfs/2016_summer.pdf Sierra Madre Historical Preservation Society, September 2016 Newsletter]</ref> With no church in the new small town Annetta Carter helped form the worship group in 1882 that became Sierra Madre Congregational Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mvobserver.com/old/MWO/v02/MWO-010507.pdf|title=THE MT. WILSON OBSERVER, January 5 - January 10, 200, Sierra Madre Turns 100, Year Long Celebration Begins, By Susan Henderso, Page 3|author=|date=|website=mvobserver.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>Annual Publications of the Historical Society of Southern California, Volume 6, page 178</ref> The ONC bell was made and installed in 1893, and has the quote on it \u201cLet him who hears come.\u201d made by Meneely Bell Foundry, Troy, NY,. The bell was presented to the Church by Mr. A.S. Bixby, from [[Bixby Knolls, Long Beach]]. The bell was used for Sunday services and funerals, but also had a civic duty, to  alert the all volunteer Fire  Department.\n\nThe original 1904 Pastor's [[parsonage]] house was on the north side of Central Avenue (about 127 W. Sierra Madre Boulevard), but as the city grew the house was now on a busy street, so in 1923 the parsonage was moved to Hermosa, just south of the main SMCC building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/histprop/40.pdf|title=40 S. Hermosa The Parsonage, 1904, By Maggie Ellis, 2014|author=|date=|website=smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nJust to the west of the Old North Church are two other historic buildings: a 1919 Old [[Mortuary]] (was Ripple Mortuary, now called the New Life Center) and the 1915 Caretaker [[American Craftsman]] home (now called the Hospitality House). Both structures were purchased by SMCC in 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mtnviewsnews.com/old/mvnews/v09/MVNews_2015_04_18.pdf|title=mtnviewsnews.com, Mountain News News, Volume 9 No. 16, Did You Ever Want To Peek Inside The Old North Church Across From Memorial Park, Saturday, April 18, 2015|author=|date=|website=mtnviewsnews.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 1928 sanctuary has stained glass windows that were given as memorials. The north side of the sanctuary has Apostles windows and on the south side are Prophets windows. The sanctuary east and west walls have two large windows, the east an Angel window with the verse \"Glory to God in the Highest.\" and the circular west window is \"Christ the Teacher,\" that was given by the Women's Society and dedicated all the children of Sierra Madre. The lower south widows were a gift from Dick and Dotty Anderson in 2008. Memorial chimes were installed in 1944 in to the tower, these played for many years on the hour.<ref>Independent Star-News Pasadena, page 8, March 20, 1966</ref>\n\nIn 1971 Sierra Madre Congregational Church and Bethany Church started the Sierra Madre Christmas Candlelight Walk. The first Candlelight Procession was led by Pastor Bob Vander Zaag of Bethany Church and Rev. Richard Anderson of Sierra Madre Congregational Church.\n\nIn September of 2018 Sierra Madre Congregational Church changed its name to Christ Church Sierra Madre.\n\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierramadrenews.net/?p=5853|title=Sierra Madre News Net  \u00bb Restored Creche Figures to \"Debut\" at Dickens Village|author=|date=|website=www.sierramadrenews.net|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierramadrenews.net/?p=21524|title=Sierra Madre News Net  \u00bb Candlelight Procession, 2015 \u2013 Photos and Video|author=|date=|website=www.sierramadrenews.net|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable pastors==\n*Marquis Lafayette Gordon MD (1843-1900), pastor 1886 to 1887. First pastor, part-time. A Medical missionary to Kyoto, Japan. He was in Sierra Madre for one year with is wife Agnes and 4 childern.<ref>[https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/agents/people/5402 Dartmouth Libraries, Gordon, Marquis Lafayette] </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/histprop/191.pdf|title=Jim Constantia, Church Historian Sierra Madre Congregational Church|author=|date=|website=smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Lucien Haskell Fray, pastor from 1887 to 1888<ref>History of Haverhill, N.H., By John Quincy Bittinger, Lucien Haskell Fray, page 325</ref> \n*Ephraim E. P. Abbott, pastor from 1888 to 1898.<ref>Biographical Sketches of the Class of 1863, Dartmouth College, By John Scales, page 130</ref><ref>The Pacific, Volume 54, Jan. 7, 1904, page 10</ref>\n*W. H. Stubbins, pastor 1898 to 1900.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/minutesannualme00unkngoog|title=Minutes of the ... Annual Meeting of the Southern California Congregational \u2026|first=|last=Southern California Congregational Conference|date=29 September 2018|publisher=T.T. Jones Co.|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>Congregationalist, Advance, Volume 106, page 781, W. H. \"Stubbins, Jan. 6, 1921</ref>\n* Rev. Charles S. Rich, pastor from 1902 to 1903.<ref>Minutes of the Annual Meeting of the Southern California Congregational Churches, 1913 Pomona, Ca., Rev. Charles S. Rich, Page 39, From Stockbridge, Mass.</ref>\n* Dr. James M. Campbell D. D., pastor from 1903 to 1912<ref>The Lutheran Quarterly, Volume 42, 1912, Page 133</ref><ref>The Continent, newspaper, Volume 43, March 28, 1912, page 429</ref><ref>Northwestern Christian Advocate, Volume 60, page 350,  March 12, 1912</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christinyou.net/pages/jmcampbell.html|title=Excerpts from the writings of James M. Campbell (1840-1926)|author=|date=|website=www.christinyou.net|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*William H. Hannaford pastor 1912, 1914-16 <ref>[http://www.ancestry.com/genealogy/records/william-h-hannaford_115412484 ancestry.com, William H Hannaford]</ref><ref>Desert Sun, Number 188, Indio Woman Honored As California Mother of 1958, Ruth writes about her father, William H Hannaford, Page 8, May 1, 1958</ref><ref>The Pacific - Volume 65, Issues 1-26 - Page 10</ref>\n*Fred Staff, Pastor from 1913 to 1914 and again from 1923 to Nov. 1925, from 1914 to 1916 he returned to Sweden, his native country. Died while pastor. He is honored in SMCC's Fred Staff room.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/congregationalye1925cong|title=The Congregational year-book|first=|last=Congregational churches in the United States. National council|date=29 September 2018|publisher=Boston, Congregational publishing society; [etc., etc.]|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://fcucc.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/April-2015-Communicator-FINAL-w-Logo-rev-p-14-plus.pdf|title=The Communicator - First Congregational Church, page 10, by Chris Steenbergen, Church Historian, April 2015|author=|date=|website=fcucc.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>The Pacific, Volume 65, Issues 1-26, page 10, 1915</ref><ref>Santa Ana Register, Page 8, November 7, 1925</ref>\n* Rev. C. C. Wilson, pastor 1914 to 1918.<ref>Wisconsin Congregational Church Life, Volumes 35-36, 1915</ref><ref>Santa Ana Register, Page 4 , November 17, 1917</ref>\n* Rev. W. J. Thompson (Rev. Dr. William J. Thompson), pastor from March 1920 to 1923 (his last church to pastor), from [[Sheffield]] came to the US in 1910, later was president of United [[Amateur Press Association]] of America.<ref>Congregational and Advance, Jan. 15, 1920, page 89 Volume 105</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/31811905/|title=Independent Star-News from Pasadena, California on August 24, 1968 \u00b7 Page 5|author=|date=|website=newspapers.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Arthur O. Pritchard, pastor at the time of the opening of the new building in 1928, Pritchard Hall is named after him. Pastor from 1926 to 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/histprop/170.pdf|title=Sierra Madre Historical Preservation Society, 170 W. Sierra Madre Blvd., Sierra Madre First Congregational Church 1928, By Maggie Ellis, 2014|author=|date=|website=smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19400621.2.17 Scarsdale Inquirer, Number 21, 21 June 1940, ''Former Pastor Honored, The Rev. Arthur O. Pritchard of Sierra Madre, California'' ]</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/brownalumnimonth1034brow|title=Brown alumni monthly|first=|last=Brown University|date=29 September 2018|publisher=Providence, Brown University [etc.]|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> From Hollywood Congregational Church<ref>Holly Leaves, Sept. 9, 1922, Hollywood, Volume 11, Issues 25-52, page 30</ref>\n* George Lindsay pastor from March 1956 to 1964, 20th pastor, (no pastor till Howell)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/31749830/|title=Independent Star-News from Pasadena, California on February 15, 1959 \u00b7 Page 72|author=|date=|website=newspapers.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>Los Angeles Times, Page 381, February 1, 1959</ref><ref>Arcadia Tribune, Page 38, August 4, 1966</ref>\n*Rev. David Howell Jr. pastor 1966 to 1968.<ref>Arcadia Tribune, Page 32, September 15, 1966</ref>\n* Richard (Dick) Anderson, Sr. Pastor for 40 years, from 1968 to 2008.  He is honored in SMCC's Anderson Terrance.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-06-29/news/mn-1097_1_sierra-madre|title=Neighborliness Shines Through in Sierra Madre|journal=Los Angeles Times|first=SCOTT|last=HARRIS|date=29 June 1991|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=LA Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mvobserver.com/old/MVO/v02/MVO_2008_08_08.pdf|title=Sierra Madre News Net, Front Page, Rev. Richard (Dick) Anderson, 40 years of Service, Aug. 8, 2008|author=|date=|website=mvobserver.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/jesusmovementits00smit|title=The Jesus Movement: Its Development and It's Relationship To The Army Chapel and Chaplains|first=Billy T.|last=Smith|date=29 December 2018|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n*James J. Stewart Jr., associate pastor, Now pastor at Journey Covenant Church, Redondo Beach, California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.covchurch.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/41/2012/07/Yearbook-AM-Minutes.pdf|title=Minutes of the 126th Annual Meeting of the Evangelical Covenant Church, June 29, 2011, Page 477|author=|date=|website=covchurch.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Ken Cromeenes, Pastor of Administration 1980s to 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/81313038/|title=The San Bernardino County Sun from San Bernardino, California on June 29, 1992 \u00b7 Page 8|author=|date=|website=newspapers.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>  \n*John Reed, associate pastor 1986 to 1996, former [[Army Chaplain]].\n*Tim Thompson, associate pastor (May 2002 \u2013 October 2008) and founder of The Church Works.<ref>[http://pastortimthompson.com/ Rev. Tim Thompson, web site]</ref><ref>Notre Dame de Namur University, VOLUME 6, NUMBER 2, MAGAZINE, page 13 Spring 2006]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Tim-Thompson-Evangelistic-Ministries-272907457830/|title=Tim Thompson Evangelistic Ministries|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Rick Bundschuh youth pastor 1978, author of ''Deep Like Me: (Or Another Failed Attempt to Walk on Water)''.<ref>Deep Like Me: (Or Another Failed Attempt to Walk on Water), By Rick Bundschuh, Foreword by Pastor Richard Anderson</ref>\n*Jim Zeilenga, pastor of assimilation and outreach from April 1987 to March 2004. Now pastor at Valencia Hills Community Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/jim-zeilenga-a090ab16|title=Jim Zeilenga on Linkedin|author=|date=|website=linkedin.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1992-06-29/news/1992181082_1_quake-sierra-madre-temblor|title=Two earthquakes rock California Biggest temblor in decades leaves 1 dead, scores hurt|author=|date=|website=baltimoresun.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Larry Mills, minister of Christian education, 2000s <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ministrytransitions.org/books/Inviting-Volunteers-To-Minister/ch1.pdf|title=It's Only Natural: An Atmospheric Approach - Sierra Madre Congregational Church Sierra Madre, California, Inviting Volunteers To Minister|author=|date=|website=ministrytransitions.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*[[John Eldredge]] associate pastor 1983-1988, now author, counselor, and lecturer on Christianity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ransomedheart.com/|title=Ransomed Heart|author=|date=|website=www.ransomedheart.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Brian Anderson, youth pastor 1987-1990, now Pastor at Mission Hills Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://missionhillschurch.com/about/staff/brian-anderson/|title=Brian Anderson - Staff - Mission Hills Church|first=Mission Hills|last=Church|date=|website=missionhillschurch.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-03-31/news/ga-838_1_world-vision|title=Fast Gives Food for Thought on World Hunger|journal=Los Angeles Times|first=BERKLEY|last=HUDSON|date=31 March 1988|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=LA Times}}</ref>\n*Steve Wiebe, youth pastor 1992-1999, now founder and director of Neighborhood Urban Family Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apu.edu/faculty/cvs/slwiebe.pdf|title=Steve Wiebe Bio|author=|date=|website=apu.edu|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.can-dokids.org/contact.html|title=Contact|author=|date=|website=NEIGHBORHOOD URBAN FAMILY CENTER|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Rick Mumford, youth pastor 2004 to 2006, now with KC Metro.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kcmetro.younglife.org/Pages/Metro-Team.aspx|title=Young Life, staff Rick Mumford|author=|date=|website=younglife.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Johnny Johnston, youth pastor 2006-2010. now Jennersville Campus Pastor, Willowdale Chapel, Kennett Square, PA<ref>[https://www.linkedin.com/in/johnny-johnston-10bb394b linkedin.com, Johnny Johnston]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/2268789|title=Youth Ministry at Fuller: Johnny Johnston|first=Fuller Theological|last=Seminary|date=17 November 2008|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=Vimeo}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lcf.squarespace.com/contact/|title=lLCF - Contact|author=|date=|website=lcf.squarespace.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Roger Van Spronsen, associate pastor 1988-2009, now pastor at Life Christian Fellowship.<ref>[http://www.providencecc.edu/academics/faculty/jan-van-spronsen/ providencecc.edu, Jan Van Spronsen]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lcf.squarespace.com/contact/|title=lLCF - Contact|author=|date=|website=lcf.squarespace.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Paul S. Beck, Sr. pastor for six years, 2008 to 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/paul-beck-5bb4796|title=linkedin.com, Paul Beck|author=|date=|website=linkedin.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Steve Miller, Intentional Interim Senior Pastor of Sierra Madre Congregational Church, 2014 to Nov. 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/steve-miller-92252814|title=linkedin.com, Steve Miller|author=|date=|website=linkedin.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Gavin Rutherford Ortlund, associate pastor (October 2014 to Nov. 2016) and former youth Pastor at SMCC (Oct. 2010-Oct 2014). Son of [[Raymond C. Ortlund, Jr.]] and Grandson of [[Raymond C. Ortlund Sr.]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gavinortlund.com/|title=Soliloquium|author=|date=|website=Soliloquium|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gavinortlund.com/2011/05/05/one-of-my-grandads-sermons/|title=One of my Grandad's Sermons|author=|date=5 May 2011|website=gavinortlund.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://henrycenter.tiu.edu/2017/05/what-does-augustine-have-to-do-with-evolution-and-the-historical-adam/|title=What Does Augustine Have to Do with Evolution & the Historical Adam? - Henry Center|author=|date=16 May 2017|website=tiu.edu|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> Now Senior Pastor at First Baptist Church of Ojai<ref>[https://www.fbcojai.org/leadership/ First Baptist Church of Ojai, Gavin Ortlund]</ref>\n*Abel Burke, youth Pastor at SMCC for 6 years (2012 to March 2018) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zs0wEO3X4oE|title=The Power of the Word - Hebrews 4|first=|last=Abel Burke|date=1 February 2017|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n* Dr. [[Hugh Ross (astrophysicist)|Hugh Ross]], pastor for outreach and [[apologetics]] from 1971 to present (part-time starting in 1987).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reasons.org/about/who-we-are/hugh-ross|title=Hugh Ross|author=|date=|website=www.reasons.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Josh Swanson, Sr. Pastor, Dec. 2017 to present, previously with Hope Church in Albuquerque, NM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smccnet.org/what-we-do-1/|title=SMCC, smccnet.org, SMCC Leadership|author=|date=|website=smccnet.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Robert Covolo, SMCC's Pastor of Theological Formation & Missional Engagement and Director of Pastoral Residency and Internship Program. 2018 to present. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smccnet.org/leadership/|title=Leadership|author=|date=|website=sierra madre congregational church|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biola.edu/directory/people/robert-covolo|title=Bob Covolo - People, Biola University|author=|date=|website=www.biola.edu|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://biola.academia.edu/RobertCovolo|title=Robert Covolo - Biola University - Academia.edu|author=|date=|website=biola.academia.edu|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Justin Sapp Director of Student and College Ministries 2018 to present. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smccnet.org/leadership/|title=Leadership|author=|date=|website=sierra madre congregational church|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/pg/justin.sapp.official/about/?ref=page_internal|title=Justin Sapp|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Episcopal Church of the Ascension (Sierra Madre, California)]]\n* [[Greater Los Angeles Area Council]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.christchurchsm.org/ Christ Church Sierra Madre, (formally Sierra Madre Congregational Church official) web site]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/christchurchsm/ facebook.com, Christ Church Sierra Madre]\n*[http://www.seedbedchurch.com/about/history-and-his-story/ Seed Bed Church, meetings at SMCC]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/pages/Jemaat-Kristen-Indonesia-Anugerah-Church/207841532661879?nr Jemaat Kristen Indonesia Anugerah Church, Church in the Old North Church, Sunday afternoons]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/jkianugerah/  JKI Anugerah - Grace Indonesian Christian Fellowship]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Old-North-Church, Sierra Madre Congregational Church}}\n[[Category:Churches in Los Angeles County, California]]\n[[Category:Sierra Madre, California| ]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1890]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1928]]\n", "text_old": "{{About| Old North Church in Sierra Madre, California, for Boston see:||Old North Church|Boston}}\n{{Infobox Historic building\n|name=Old North Church <br/>Christ Church Sierra Madre - ''Sierra Madre Congregational Church'' \n|image=Old_North_Church,_Sierra_Madre,_California.jpg\n|caption=Old North Church, Sierra Madre, California, a historic landmark.\n|location_town=[[Sierra Madre, California]]\n|location_country=[[United States]]\n| designations        = Sierra Madre Historic Landmark #40\n|architect=\n|construction_start_date= April 1890\n|completion_date= Dec. 14, 1890\n|date_demolished=\n|cost=$3,300\n| altitude            = {{convert|263|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n|structural_system= Wood\n| status              = Used for Youth Groups<br/> and Indonesia Church: Jemaat Kristen\n| current_tenants = Christ Church Sierra Madre, formerly called ''Sierra Madre Congregational Church''\n|style=[[Georgian architecture]]\n| map_type            = Los Angeles\n| map_alt             = \n| map_caption         = Old North Church in Sierra Madre, California\n| coordinates    = {{coord|34.1622306|-118.0566944|region:US-PA_type:landmark|display=inline}}\n| website = https://www.christchurchsm.org\n}}\n\n[[Image:Sierra Madre Congregational Church 1928.jpg|right|thumb|250px|'''Christ Church Sierra Madre - Sierra Madre Congregational Church''', a historic landmark <br/>Sierra Madre Historic Landmark #44 <br/> Architect: Marsh, Smith, & Powell <BR/> Construction started: 1925 <br/> Construction completion: 1928<BR/> Total Cost: $80,000 <br/>*Pritchard Hall and Admin building $40,000<br/>*Sanctuary $35,000<br/>*Furniture $5,000<br/>Architectural style: Romanesque Revival<BR/>Across the Street from Old North Church]]\n\n[[File:Old-North-Church-Sierra-Madre-California-1890.jpg|thumb|right|Old North Church in Sierra Madre at completion in 1890]]\n\n[[Image:Original Sierra Madre City Library.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Original 1887 Sierra Madre City Library on Central Ave, renamed Sierra Madre Blvd in 1936. Sierra Madre Congregational Church temporary meeting place in 1889.]]\n\n[[Image:Sierra Madre Town Hall 1895.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Original 1895 Sierra Madre Town Hall (with Cigar Factory next door) at Baldwin and Central Ave (now a gas station) . Sierra Madre Congregational Church temporary meeting place.]]\n\n[[Image:Central Ave Sierra Madre CA 1904-Old North Church .jpg|right|thumb|250px|Central Ave, Sierra Madre CA in 1905. A mule team is grading the Ave for the installation of the 1906 Pacific Electric street car, in the background is the Old North Church with the original barn roof bell tower.]]\n\n[[File:OldNorthChurchSierraMadreCalifornia1909.jpg|thumb|right|Old North Church Sierra Madre California 1909]]\n\n[[Image:Sierra_Madre_Memorial_Park_-_SM_Blvd_and_Hermosa.jpg|thumb|right|[[Sierra Madre Memorial Park]] at Sierra Madre Blvd and Hermosa looking North. From foreground to back ground: Weeping Wall Veterans Memorial, Sierra Madre Veterans Time Capsule bench, 1905 World War I Cannon,  Sierra Madre Boulevard, The Old North Church and the [[San Gabriel Mountains]]]].\n\n[[File:OldNorthChurchSierra_MadreCalifornia1906.jpg|thumb|right|Old North Church in 1906, looking North on Hermosa Ave]]\n\n'''Old North Church''' (ONC) is in [[Sierra Madre, California]].\nOld North Church is a [[Historic site|historic landmark]] building built in 1890, one of the oldest [[Church (building)|church]]es and buildings in Sierra Madre. The Old North Church is owned by it builder '''Sierra Madre Congregational Church''', called '''First Congregational Church of Sierra Madre''' at the time of completion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.geoview.info/old_north_church,5379055|title=Old North Church church, California, United States|author=|date=|website=us.geoview.info|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> It is site #45 on Sierra Madre designated historical landmarks list. There are forty-eight properties listed on Sierra Madre's Designated Historical Properties List.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofsierramadre.com/services/planning_and_building/historic_preservation|title=Historic Preservation - Sierra Madre|author=|date=|website=www.cityofsierramadre.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/historic-properties.html|title=Sierra Madre:  Historic Properties|author=|date=|website=www.smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> In September of 2018 Sierra Madre Congregational Church changed its name to '''Christ Church Sierra Madre'''.<ref>[https://www.christchurchsm.org/ Christ Church Sierra Madre, official web site]</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe Old North Church was constructed by hand with local wood. It is located on the north side of the current [[Sierra Madre Blvd]] at Hermosa. In 1890 Sierra Madre Blvd was a dirt street called Central Avenue. Old North Church is currently owned by its builder, Sierra Madre Congregational Church. The Old North Church is closely linked with the early settlement of Sierra Madre.<ref name=\"smccnet\">{{cite web|url=http://christchurchsm.org/about/|title=christchurchsm.org/about/, Sierra Madre Congregational Church-(SMCC), Church History, EARLY YEARS|author=|date=|website=smccnet.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>  The community of Sierra Madre was established in the fall of 1881. Sierra Madre Congregational Church started as a [[Sunday School]] class in February 1882. Without a building of its own, the church originally met in the city's original 1882 [[one-room school]]house at the corner of Hermosa and Live Oak, now called [[Orange Grove Boulevard (Pasadena)|Orange Grove]]. To use the schoolhouse as a church on Sunday mornings, the [[pump organ]], [[Hymnal|hymnbooks]], and winter [[firewood]] were transported to the schoolhouse by the attendees. The following years the Church met in the original [[City Hall]] at the corner Baldwin and Central Ave (Sierra Madre), then the original city [[library]] (1889), located at the current library site.  With the completion of the Old North Church in 1890, the church had its own meeting spot. Congregational Church of Sierra Madre was officially established on March 27, 1886 as a [[nondenominational church]] [[congregational church]], with 13 founding members, called ''First Congregational Church of Sierra Madre'' then. One of the 13 founding members was Mrs. Annetta M. Carter, wife of the city founder Nathaniel Coburn Carter. From 1908 to 1910 the Old North Church was expanded with the addition of new meeting rooms.<ref name=\"smccnet\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/histprop/191.pdf|title=Sierra Madre Historical Preservation Society, Old North Church|author=|date=|website=smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/photo-gallery.html|title=Photo Gallery|author=|date=|website=www.smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Church's second, and current, main building was built across the street. Construction of the new building started in 1926 with Pritchard Hall and was completed in 1928 with the new sanctuary dedicated on June 17, 1928. The sanctuary cornerstone was laid on Feb. 19, 1928.<ref name=\"smccnet\" /> The 1928 Church building is also a Sierra Madre designated historical landmark, as site #39. Having outgrown the Old North Church in the mid 1920s, the Congregational Church of Sierra Madre built a new stone Church in a [[Romanesque Revival architecture]] style, designed by Marsh, Smith, & Powell.<ref name=\"smcctimeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofsierramadre.com/services/library/local_history/sierra_madre_timeline/|title=Sierra Madre Historical Timeline - Sierra Madre|author=|date=|website=www.cityofsierramadre.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> Later after the move, the Old North Church was rented to the First [[Church of the Nazarene]] in 1939, then purchased by them in 1942. After the Church of the Nazarene outgrew the Old North Church, it was sold back to Sierra Madre Congregational Church in 1976.<ref>City of Sierra Madre, General Plan Technical Background Report, September 2012, PDF file, cityofsierramadre.com/documents</ref> Congregational Church purchased back the Old North Church for the use of its youth and children, its current role.  Sierra Madre's [[Cub Scout#United States|Cub Scouts]] Pack 373, and some of [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scouts]] Troop 373, meetings are held in the Old North Church. Troop 373 was founded in the Old North Church in 1924. [[Cub Scout#United States|Cub Scouts]] Pack 373 was started in 1971. Troop 373 was one of the founders of the Sierra Madre [[Fourth of July]] [[parade]] that then ran from historic [[Sierra Madre Memorial Park]] (across the street from the ONC) to historic [[Sierra Madre Pioneer Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierramadretroop373.org|title=Pack 373 Dens|first=|last=Pack 373|date=|website=Pack373|accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierramadretroop373.org|title=Boy Scouts Troop 373|first=|last=Troop 373|date=|website=Troop373|accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Old North Church survived the [[1991 Sierra Madre earthquake]] relatively undamaged. The 1928 building had damage to the [[bell tower]], which was torn down brick by brick and rebuilt.  The original ONC bell tower was built with a [[barn]] shaped roof, modeled after a Dutch church in Holland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/photo-gallery.html|title=Photo Gallery|author=|date=|website=www.smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref> Later the Church of the Nazarene changed the bell tower to have a more classic pointed [[spire]]. The bell tower housed the 1893 bell weighing 517 pounds, in 1928 the bell was moved to the new south bell tower.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://s-media-cache-ak0.pinimg.com/736x/b8/68/4d/b8684dc5cc8bd15109129e84dd54b002--sierra-gabriel.jpg|title=Old North Church Barn roof|author=|date=|website=pinimg.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>Independent Star-News from Pasadena, California, Page 72, February 15, 1959</ref>\n\nIn 1890 Old North Church attendees had to walk, ride a horse or ride in a horse buggy. In January 1906 the [[Pacific Electric]] street car was installed and rolled in front of the Old North Church, on the [[Sierra Madre (Pacific Electric)|Sierra Madre line]], each day from January 1, 1906 till service ended on October 6, 1950.<ref name=\"smcctimeline\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.erha.org/pelines/pensm.htm|title=Pacific Electric Sierra Madre Line|author=|date=|website=www.erha.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nMrs. Annetta M. Carter (Feb, 10, 1846-Sept. 24, 1937), wife of Nathaniel Coburn Carter (Jan. 24, 1840 - Sept. 2, 1904), was key founder of Sierra Madre Congregational Church.<ref name=\"smccnet\" />Nathaniel and Annetta married in Feb. of 1864 and had 5 children: Florence, (now Mrs. William H. Mead); Arthur N. (b1868), Julia F., Anita E. (the first child born in the Sierra Madre, (b1883, m1910 to Holt R Gregory) and Phillip C (b1885). Annetta M. Pierce (Carter) and Nathaniel both were natives of [[Lowell, Massachusetts]], Nathaniel came to California for his health in 1871.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Nathaniel-Carter/6000000033555250826|title=Nathaniel Coburn Carter|author=|date=|website=geni_family_tree|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1996-01-23/local/me-27784_1_sierra-madre LA Times, Community Profile: Sierra Madre, January 23, 1996, by CECILIA RASMUSSEN]</ref><ref>Annual Publication of the Historical Society of Southern California, Volume 6, Page 178, In memory of Nathaniel Coburn Carter</ref> In February 1881, Nathaniel Carter purchased the original 1103 acres that comprised the new city of Sierra Madre. The land was acquired in three purchases: 845 acres of [[Rancho Santa Anita]] from [[Lucky Baldwin]], 108 acres from the [[Southern Pacific Railroad Company]] and 150 acres from John Richardson (1811-Aug. 9, 1884).<ref>[http://www.smhps.org/archivedpdfs/2016_summer.pdf Sierra Madre Historical Preservation Society, September 2016 Newsletter]</ref> With no church in the new small town Annetta Carter helped form the worship group in 1882 that became Sierra Madre Congregational Church.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mvobserver.com/old/MWO/v02/MWO-010507.pdf|title=THE MT. WILSON OBSERVER, January 5 - January 10, 200, Sierra Madre Turns 100, Year Long Celebration Begins, By Susan Henderso, Page 3|author=|date=|website=mvobserver.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>Annual Publications of the Historical Society of Southern California, Volume 6, page 178</ref> The ONC bell was made and installed in 1893, and has the quote on it \u201cLet him who hears come.\u201d made by Meneely Bell Foundry, Troy, NY,. The bell was presented to the Church by Mr. A.S. Bixby, from [[Bixby Knolls, Long Beach]]. The bell was used for Sunday services and funerals, but also had a civic duty, to  alert the all volunteer Fire  Department.\n\nThe original 1904 Pastor's [[parsonage]] house was on the north side of Central Avenue (about 127 W. Sierra Madre Boulevard), but as the city grew the house was now on a busy street, so in 1923 the parsonage was moved to Hermosa, just south of the main SMCC building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/histprop/40.pdf|title=40 S. Hermosa The Parsonage, 1904, By Maggie Ellis, 2014|author=|date=|website=smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nJust to the west of the Old North Church are two other historic buildings: a 1919 Old [[Mortuary]] (was Ripple Mortuary, now called the New Life Center) and the 1915 Caretaker [[American Craftsman]] home (now called the Hospitality House). Both structures were purchased by SMCC in 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mtnviewsnews.com/old/mvnews/v09/MVNews_2015_04_18.pdf|title=mtnviewsnews.com, Mountain News News, Volume 9 No. 16, Did You Ever Want To Peek Inside The Old North Church Across From Memorial Park, Saturday, April 18, 2015|author=|date=|website=mtnviewsnews.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe 1928 sanctuary has stained glass windows that were given as memorials. The north side of the sanctuary has Apostles windows and on the south side are Prophets windows. The sanctuary east and west walls have two large windows, the east an Angel window with the verse \"Glory to God in the Highest.\" and the circular west window is \"Christ the Teacher,\" that was given by the Women's Society and dedicated all the children of Sierra Madre. The lower south widows were a gift from Dick and Dotty Anderson in 2008. Memorial chimes were installed in 1944 in to the tower, these played for many years on the hour.<ref>Independent Star-News Pasadena, page 8, March 20, 1966</ref>\n\nIn 1971 Sierra Madre Congregational Church and Bethany Church started the Sierra Madre Christmas Candlelight Walk. The first Candlelight Procession was led by Pastor Bob Vander Zaag of Bethany Church and Rev. Richard Anderson of Sierra Madre Congregational Church.\n\nIn September of 2018 Sierra Madre Congregational Church changed its name to Christ Church Sierra Madre.\n\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierramadrenews.net/?p=5853|title=Sierra Madre News Net  \u00bb Restored Creche Figures to \"Debut\" at Dickens Village|author=|date=|website=www.sierramadrenews.net|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sierramadrenews.net/?p=21524|title=Sierra Madre News Net  \u00bb Candlelight Procession, 2015 \u2013 Photos and Video|author=|date=|website=www.sierramadrenews.net|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notable pastors==\n*Marquis Lafayette Gordon MD (1843-1900), pastor 1886 to 1887. First pastor. A Medical missionary to Kyoto, Japan. He was in Sierra Madre for one year with is wife Agnes and 4 childern.<ref>[https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/agents/people/5402 Dartmouth Libraries, Gordon, Marquis Lafayette] </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/histprop/191.pdf|title=Jim Constantia, Church Historian Sierra Madre Congregational Church|author=|date=|website=smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Lucien Haskell Fray, pastor from 1887 to 1888<ref>History of Haverhill, N.H., By John Quincy Bittinger, Lucien Haskell Fray, page 325</ref> \n*Ephraim E. P. Abbott, pastor from 1888 to 1898.<ref>Biographical Sketches of the Class of 1863, Dartmouth College, By John Scales, page 130</ref><ref>The Pacific, Volume 54, Jan. 7, 1904, page 10</ref>\n*W. H. Stubbins, pastor 1898 to 1900.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/minutesannualme00unkngoog|title=Minutes of the ... Annual Meeting of the Southern California Congregational \u2026|first=|last=Southern California Congregational Conference|date=29 September 2018|publisher=T.T. Jones Co.|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>Congregationalist, Advance, Volume 106, page 781, W. H. \"Stubbins, Jan. 6, 1921</ref>\n* Rev. Charles S. Rich, pastor from 1902 to 1903.<ref>Minutes of the Annual Meeting of the Southern California Congregational Churches, 1913 Pomona, Ca., Rev. Charles S. Rich, Page 39, From Stockbridge, Mass.</ref>\n* Dr. James M. Campbell D. D., pastor from 1903 to 1912<ref>The Lutheran Quarterly, Volume 42, 1912, Page 133</ref><ref>The Continent, newspaper, Volume 43, March 28, 1912, page 429</ref><ref>Northwestern Christian Advocate, Volume 60, page 350,  March 12, 1912</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christinyou.net/pages/jmcampbell.html|title=Excerpts from the writings of James M. Campbell (1840-1926)|author=|date=|website=www.christinyou.net|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n*William H. Hannaford pastor 1912, 1914-16 <ref>[http://www.ancestry.com/genealogy/records/william-h-hannaford_115412484 ancestry.com, William H Hannaford]</ref><ref>Desert Sun, Number 188, Indio Woman Honored As California Mother of 1958, Ruth writes about her father, William H Hannaford, Page 8, May 1, 1958</ref><ref>The Pacific - Volume 65, Issues 1-26 - Page 10</ref>\n*Fred Staff, Pastor from 1913 to 1914 and again from 1923 to Nov. 1925, from 1914 to 1916 he returned to Sweden, his native country. Died while pastor. He is honored in SMCC's Fred Staff room.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/congregationalye1925cong|title=The Congregational year-book|first=|last=Congregational churches in the United States. National council|date=29 September 2018|publisher=Boston, Congregational publishing society; [etc., etc.]|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://fcucc.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/April-2015-Communicator-FINAL-w-Logo-rev-p-14-plus.pdf|title=The Communicator - First Congregational Church, page 10, by Chris Steenbergen, Church Historian, April 2015|author=|date=|website=fcucc.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>The Pacific, Volume 65, Issues 1-26, page 10, 1915</ref><ref>Santa Ana Register, Page 8, November 7, 1925</ref>\n* Rev. C. C. Wilson, pastor 1914 to 1918.<ref>Wisconsin Congregational Church Life, Volumes 35-36, 1915</ref><ref>Santa Ana Register, Page 4 , November 17, 1917</ref>\n* Rev. W. J. Thompson (Rev. Dr. William J. Thompson), pastor from March 1920 to 1923 (his last church to pastor), from [[Sheffield]] came to the US in 1910, later was president of United [[Amateur Press Association]] of America.<ref>Congregational and Advance, Jan. 15, 1920, page 89 Volume 105</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/31811905/|title=Independent Star-News from Pasadena, California on August 24, 1968 \u00b7 Page 5|author=|date=|website=newspapers.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Arthur O. Pritchard, pastor at the time of the opening of the new building in 1928, Pritchard Hall is named after him. Pastor from 1926 to 1940.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smhps.org/histprop/170.pdf|title=Sierra Madre Historical Preservation Society, 170 W. Sierra Madre Blvd., Sierra Madre First Congregational Church 1928, By Maggie Ellis, 2014|author=|date=|website=smhps.org|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19400621.2.17 Scarsdale Inquirer, Number 21, 21 June 1940, ''Former Pastor Honored, The Rev. Arthur O. Pritchard of Sierra Madre, California'' ]</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/brownalumnimonth1034brow|title=Brown alumni monthly|first=|last=Brown University|date=29 September 2018|publisher=Providence, Brown University [etc.]|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> From Hollywood Congregational Church<ref>Holly Leaves, Sept. 9, 1922, Hollywood, Volume 11, Issues 25-52, page 30</ref>\n* George Lindsay pastor from March 1956 to 1964, 20th pastor, (no pastor till Howell)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/31749830/|title=Independent Star-News from Pasadena, California on February 15, 1959 \u00b7 Page 72|author=|date=|website=newspapers.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>Los Angeles Times, Page 381, February 1, 1959</ref><ref>Arcadia Tribune, Page 38, August 4, 1966</ref>\n*Rev. David Howell Jr. pastor 1966 to 1968.<ref>Arcadia Tribune, Page 32, September 15, 1966</ref>\n* Richard (Dick) Anderson, Sr. Pastor for 40 years, from 1968 to 2008.  He is honored in SMCC's Anderson Terrance.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-06-29/news/mn-1097_1_sierra-madre|title=Neighborliness Shines Through in Sierra Madre|journal=Los Angeles Times|first=SCOTT|last=HARRIS|date=29 June 1991|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=LA Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mvobserver.com/old/MVO/v02/MVO_2008_08_08.pdf|title=Sierra Madre News Net, Front Page, Rev. Richard (Dick) Anderson, 40 years of Service, Aug. 8, 2008|author=|date=|website=mvobserver.com|accessdate=29 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/jesusmovementits00smit|title=The Jesus Movement: Its Development and It's Relationship To The Army Chapel and Chaplains|first=Billy T.|last=Smith|date=29 December 2018|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2018|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n*James J. Stewart Jr., associate pastor, Now pastor at Journey Covenant Church, Redondo Beach, California.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.covchurch.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/41/2012/07/Yearbook-AM-Minutes.pdf|title=Minutes of the 126th Annual Meeting of the Evangelical Covenant Church, June 29, 2011, Page 477|author=|date=|